mily             = [[List of The Big Bang Theory characters#Mary Cooper|Mary Cooper]] (mother)<br>George Cooper Sr. (father, deceased as of ''Big Bang Theory'' timeline)<br>[[List of The Big Bang Theory characters#Missy Cooper|Missy Cooper]] (twin sister)<br>George \"Georgie\" Cooper Jr. (brother)<br>Missy's unnamed son (nephew)<br>Constance \"Connie\" Tucker/\"Meemaw\"<ref name=\"sheldonS1E17\">''[[Young Sheldon]]'' episode \"Jiu-Jitsu, Bubble Wrap, and Yoo-Hoo\"</ref> (maternal grandmother)<br>Charles \"Charlie\" Tucker/\"Pop Pop\" (maternal grandfather)\n| gender             = Male\n| nicknames          = Shelley, (family, friends) Shelley Bean, (mother) Moon Pie (grandmother)\n| nationality        = American\n| religion           = {{plainlist|\n* \"Mathology\" (his invention)\n}}\n}}\n'''<!-- Per  WP:CREDENTIAL, do not include \"Dr.\" or \"Doctor\" here. -->Sheldon Lee Cooper'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbs.com/shows/big_bang_theory/video/mwSWQujTYBsrVlLkz_Qimtolt3mBbJ5e/the-big-bang-theory-the-inspiration-deprivation/|title=The Inspiration Deprivation|date=Apr 18, 2019|website=CBS}}</ref><ref name=1x12>{{cite episode|title=The Jerusalem Duality|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 1)#ep12|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=April 14, 2008|season=1|number=12|minutes=}}</ref><!-- Do not add further credentials here. For a fuller explanation see Talk:Sheldon Cooper/Archive 1#Sheldon's postnominals --> [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]], [[Doctor of Science|Sc.D.]],<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Love Car Displacement|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 4)#ep76|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=January 20, 2011|season=4|number=13|minutes=16:39}}</ref> is a fictional character in the [[CBS]] television series ''[[The Big Bang Theory]]'' and its spinoff series ''[[Young Sheldon]]'', portrayed by actors [[Jim Parsons]] in ''The Big Bang Theory'' and [[Iain Armitage]] in ''Young Sheldon'' (with Parsons as the latter series' narrator).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/03/the-big-bang-theory-sheldon-spinoff-iain-armitage-zoe-perry-cast-1202034391/|title='Big Bang' Sheldon Spinoff Inches Closer With Iain Armitage & Zoe Perry Castings|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=March 2, 2017|accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref> For his portrayal, Parsons has won four [[Primetime Emmy Award]]s, a [[Golden Globe Award]], a [[TCA Awards|TCA Award]], and two [[Critics' Choice Television Award]]s. The character's childhood is the focus of ''Young Sheldon'': the series' first season is set in 1989 when nine-year-old [[child prodigy|prodigy]] Sheldon has skipped ahead five grades, to start high school alongside his older brother.\n\nThe adult Sheldon is a senior [[Theoretical physics|theoretical physicist]] at [[California Institute of Technology|The California Institute of Technology]] (Caltech), and for the first ten seasons of ''The Big Bang Theory'' shares an apartment with his colleague and best friend, [[Leonard Hofstadter]] ([[Johnny Galecki]]); they are also friends and coworkers with [[Howard Wolowitz]] ([[Simon Helberg]]) and [[Raj Koothrappali]] ([[Kunal Nayyar]]). In season 10, Sheldon moves across the hall with his girlfriend [[List of The Big Bang Theory characters#Amy|Amy]] ([[Mayim Bialik]]), in the former apartment of Leonard's wife [[Penny (The Big Bang Theory)|Penny]] ([[Kaley Cuoco]]).<ref name=\"The Veracity Elasticity\">{{cite episode|title=The Veracity Elasticity|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 10)#ep7|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=October 17, 2016|season=10|number=7}}</ref> He has a genius-level IQ, but displays a fundamental lack of [[social skills]], a tenuous understanding of humor, and difficulty recognizing [[irony]] and [[sarcasm]] in other people, although he himself often employs them. He exhibits highly idiosyncratic behavior and a general lack of [[humility]], [[empathy]], and [[toleration]]. These characteristics provide the majority of the humor involving him, which has caused him to be described as the show's [[breakout character]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/876/876616p1.html|title=The Big Bang Theory: Season 1 Review|work=[[IGN]]|date=May 27, 2007|access-date=January 13, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-01-11/entertainment/1001100121_1_big-bang-theory-audience-nerds|title=Oak Park native finally gets the girl in 'Big Bang'|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=January 11, 2010|accessdate=January 13, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"av\">{{cite web|url=https://www.avclub.com/articles/the-griffin-equivalency,13255/|title=The Griffin Equivalency|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=October 13, 2008|access-date=October 6, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"EW2\"/> Some viewers have asserted that Sheldon's personality is consistent with [[Asperger syndrome]] and [[obsessive\u2013compulsive disorder]].<ref name=\"av\"/><ref name=SA>{{cite web|last=Waldman|first=Allison|url=http://www.aoltv.com/2009/08/14/come-up-with-a-new-theory-sheldon-does-not-have-aspergers|title=Come up with a new theory: Sheldon does NOT have Asperger's|date=August 14, 2009|publisher=aoltv.com|accessdate=February 5, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523181231/http://www.aoltv.com/2009/08/14/come-up-with-a-new-theory-sheldon-does-not-have-aspergers/|archivedate=May 23, 2012}}</ref> Co-creator [[Bill Prady]] has stated that Sheldon's character was neither conceived nor developed with regard to any of these traits,<ref name=SA/> although Parsons has said that in his opinion, Sheldon \"couldn't display ''more'' traits\" of Asperger's.\n\n== Creation and casting ==\nThe character of Sheldon Cooper was inspired by a computer programmer personally known to series co-creator Bill Prady.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thetvaddict.com/2009/04/17/paley-festival-recap-%E2%80%9809-the-big-bang-theory/|title=Paley Festival Recap '09: The Big Bang Theory|work=theTVaddict.com|date=April 17, 2009|accessdate=January 20, 2010}}</ref> He is named in honor of actor/producer [[Sheldon Leonard]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weblogs.variety.com/season_pass/2009/05/big-bang-theory-we-didnt-anticipate-how-protective-the-audience-would-feel-toward-our-guys.html|title='Big Bang Theory': 'We didn't anticipate how protective the audience would feel about our guys'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=May 5, 2009|accessdate=February 5, 2010|quote=''Q. Are Sheldon and Leonard named after the brilliant (producer) Sheldon Leonard of \"The Andy Griffith Show\", \"The Danny Thomas Show\", \"The Dick Van Dyke Show\", \"My Favorite Martian\" and \"I Spy?\" (Binnie)'' A. Yep. Chuck and I are both fans. Chuck's idea.}}</ref> and Nobel Prize Laureate [[Leon Cooper]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vos.lavoz.com.ar/content/la-formula-perfecta-del-humor-0|title=The Big Bang Theory, la f\u00f3rmula perfecta del humor}}</ref> [[Chuck Lorre]] originally intended [[Johnny Galecki]] to play the role, but Galecki thought he would be \"better suited\" for the character of Leonard.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.collider.com/entertainment/interviews/article.asp/aid/11261/tcid/1|title=Johnny Galecki Exclusive Video Interview  \u2013 The Big Bang Theory|work=collider.com|date=March 15, 2009|accessdate=January 20, 2010}}</ref> Lorre said that when [[Jim Parsons]] auditioned for the role, he was \"so startlingly good\" that he was asked to reaudition \"to make sure he hadn't gotten lucky\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/arts/tv/features/59213/|title=The Science Guy|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|author=Emma Rosenblum|date=September 20, 2009|accessdate=January 20, 2010}}</ref> Sheldon is one of only four characters to appear in every episode of the series along with Leonard, Howard and Raj.\n\n==Characterization==\n\n=== Early life ===\nSheldon was raised in [[Galveston, Texas]]<ref name=\"S02E09\">{{cite episode|title=The White Asparagus Triangulation|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 2)#ep26|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=November 24, 2008|season=2|number=9|minutes=04:15}}</ref> along with his older brother, [[George Cooper, Jr.|George Jr.]], and [[Twin|fraternal twin]] sister, Missy, by his mother, Mary Cooper, an overtly devout Baptist; and his father, [[George Cooper, Sr.|George Cooper]], a football coach.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mondaymondaynetwork.com/entertainment/the-family-dynasty-part-1-sheldon-coopers-family/|title=The Family Dynasty \u2013 Part 1: Sheldon Cooper\u2019s Family|date=2016-11-16|work=MondayMondayNetwork.com|access-date=2018-06-09|language=en-US}}</ref> Sheldon once got his father fired when he told Mr. Hinckley, a store owner, that George was stealing from the cash register.<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Sales Call Sublimation|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 9)#ep12|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=January 7, 2015|season=9|number=12}}</ref> In ''Young Sheldon'', this is [[retcon]]ned: his father is a football coach who was fired from his coaching position in Galveston because he disclosed that other coaches were illegally recruiting players to their school, forcing the family to return to Medford, a fictional town in [[East Texas]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.texasmonthly.com/the-culture/young-sheldon/|title=Jim Parsons Returns With \u2018Young Sheldon\u2019|last=Kelly|first=Christopher|date=September 21, 2017|website=Texas Monthly|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200413105954/https://www.texasmonthly.com/the-culture/young-sheldon/|archive-date=April 13, 2020|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref> He does drink, mostly beer, but is a loving father who is trying to understand his intellectually gifted son. The only member of his family to have actively encouraged his work in science was his maternal grandfather, whom he cherished and affectionately called \"Pop-Pop\", and who died when Sheldon was five years old. Pop-Pop's loss is what caused Sheldon to despise Christmas when his Christmas wish to bring Pop-Pop back didn't come true. Sheldon's closest relative is his maternal grandmother whom he affectionately calls \"Meemaw\", and who in turn calls him \"Moon Pie\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mondaymondaynetwork.com/entertainment/family-dynasty-part-2-sheldon-coopers-family/|title=The Family Dynasty Part 2: Sheldon Cooper\u2019s Family|date=2016-11-16|work=MondayMondayNetwork.com|access-date=2018-06-09|language=en-US}}</ref> His aunt was also said to have encouraged his work in science by giving him medical equipment, \"in case his work in physics failed, he'd have a 'trade' to fall back on\".\n\nSheldon was interested in science from an early age, and was a [[child prodigy]],<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Creepy Candy Coating Corollary|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 3)#ep45|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=October 19, 2009|season=3|number=5}}</ref> although due to his behavioral quirks and his lack of humility about his superior intellect, he was bullied by classmates and neighbors. Sheldon entered college at the age of eleven,<ref name=\"S01E05\">{{cite episode|title=The Hamburger Postulate|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 1)#ep5|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=October 22, 2007|season=1|number=5}}</ref> and at age fourteen he graduated from college ''[[Latin honors|summa cum laude]]''.<ref name=\"S03E18\">{{cite episode|title=The Pants Alternative|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 3)#ep18|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=March 22, 2010|season=3|number=18}}</ref> For a long time, the college he went to for undergraduate studies had not been revealed, but he always felt it was superior to his fellow ''Big Bang Theory'' colleagues' alma maters of Princeton (Leonard), MIT (Howard) and Harvard (Amy); however, it is implied in \"The Tam Turbulence\" (Season 12, Episode 4) that Sheldon is in fact a Caltech alumnus. From then, he worked on his doctorate, was a visiting professor at the [[University of Heidelberg]] in Germany, was the youngest person at the time to receive the Stevenson Award,<ref name=1x12 /> and has appeared on the cover of ''[[Journal of Physical Chemistry A]]''.<ref name=\"S10E14\">{{cite episode|title=The Emotion Detection Automation|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 10)#ep14|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=February 7, 2017|season=10|number=14}}</ref> Sheldon is now a theoretical physicist doing research at [[Caltech]], although he stated in ''Young Sheldon'' that he couldn't see himself living in California due to their carefree lifestyle.\n\n=== Personality ===\n{{redirect|Bazinga|the jellyfish genus|Bazinga (genus)|the YouTuber|Behzinga}}\nLike Leonard, Raj, and Howard, Sheldon is characterized as being highly intelligent, but he tends to display childish qualities, such as extreme stubbornness, meanness, and a lack of [[common sense]]. It is claimed by Bernadette that the reason Sheldon is sometimes mean is because the part of his brain that tells him it is wrong to be mean is \"getting a [[wedgie]] from the rest of his brain\".<ref>''[[The Big Bang Theory (season 5)|s5 e21, The Hawking Excitation]]''</ref> Although, in season 8's \"The Space Probe Disintegration\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mondaymondaynetwork.com/entertainment/big-bang-theory-sheldon-bloopers/|title=The Big Bang Theory Sheldon Bloopers|date=2018-01-28|work=MondayMondayNetwork.com|access-date=2018-06-09|language=en-US}}</ref> Sheldon tearfully admits to Leonard that he ''is'' aware of his peculiarities and how his behavior comes across. The first four episodes of ''The Big Bang Theory'' portray Sheldon slightly inconsistently with respect to his later characterization, in which he is depicted as rather witty and sarcastic, and slightly flirtatious towards Penny in the pilot episode: according to Prady, the character \"began to evolve after episode five or so and became his own thing\".<ref name=\"squad\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvsquad.com/2009/08/14/come-up-with-a-new-theory-sheldon-does-not-have-aspergers|title=Come up with a new theory: Sheldon does NOT have Asperger's|publisher=[[TV Squad]]|date=August 14, 2009|accessdate=October 6, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817125113/http://www.tvsquad.com/2009/08/14/come-up-with-a-new-theory-sheldon-does-not-have-aspergers|archivedate=August 17, 2009}}</ref>\n\nSheldon possesses an [[eidetic memory]] and an IQ of 187,<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Pancake Batter Anomaly|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 1)#ep11|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=March 31, 2008|season=1|number=11|minutes=09:58|quote=Penny, I have an IQ of 187}}</ref> although he claims his IQ cannot be accurately measured by normal tests.<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Codpiece Topology|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 2)#ep19|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=September 29, 2008|season=2|number=2|minutes=08:20}}</ref> He originally claimed to have a master's degree and two [[Doctorate|doctoral degrees]], but this list has increased.<ref name=S01E02>{{cite episode|title=The Big Bran Hypothesis|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 1)#ep2|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=October 1, 2007|season=1|number=2|minutes=16:00}}</ref><ref name=S04E01>{{cite episode|title=The Robotic Manipulation|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 4)#ep64|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=September 23, 2010|season=4|number=1|minutes=09:36}}</ref> Sheldon has an extensive general knowledge in many subjects including physics, chemistry, biology, astronomy, [[cosmology]], algebra, calculus, economics, computers, [[vexillology]], engineering, history, geography, linguistics, programming in [[Java (programming language)|Java]], geology (although he mostly despises it and geologists \u2013 it is revealed early in ''Young Sheldon'' that this might have more to do with an unfortunate incident with an older female classmate than any fault of the subject), [[American football]], trains, and in addition to being fluent in [[Klingon language|Klingon]], has some knowledge of Swedish,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbs.com/shows/big_bang_theory/video/mwSWQujTYBsrVlLkz_Qimtolt3mBbJ5e/the-big-bang-theory-the-inspiration-deprivation/|title=Watch The Big Bang Theory Season 12 Episode 19: The Inspiration Deprivation - Full show on CBS All Access|website=www.cbs.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-20}}</ref> Finnish, Hindi and Mandarin.<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Creepy Candy Coating Corollary|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 3)#ep5|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=October 19, 2009|season=3|number=5|minutes=13:55}}</ref> It is also revealed in ''Young Sheldon'' that he is proficient in [[Spanish language|Spanish]]. He also shows great talent in music, knowing how to play the piano (as does Parsons in real life), the bongos, the [[Recorder (musical instrument)|recorder]], [[theremin]] (which Parsons learned to play in real life), shows some skill in [[Tuvan throat singing]] and also has perfect pitch.<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Bon Voyage Reaction|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 6)#ep24|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=May 16, 2013|season=6|number=24}}</ref>  Although his friends have similar intellects to him, his eccentricities, stubbornness, and large ego (Sheldon frequently points out his superiority on a daily basis and does not treat anyone as his equal, implying he suffers from [[narcissistic personality disorder]]) frequently frustrate them. Sheldon occasionally uses slang (in a very unnatural fashion) and follows jokes with his [[catchphrase]] \"Bazinga!\", which is now an officially registered trademark of [[Warner Bros.]]<ref name=trademarkia>{{cite web|title=Bazinga!|author=Warner Bros. Entertainment Inc.|url=http://www.trademarkia.com/bazinga-85210353.html|accessdate=September 24, 2011}}</ref><ref name=USPTO>{{cite web|title=USPTO Trademark Status and Document Retrieval|url=http://tsdr.uspto.gov/#caseNumber=85210239&caseType=SERIAL_NO&searchType=statusSearch|accessdate=February 18, 2013}}</ref> He is uncomfortable with human physical contact and has [[Mysophobia|germophobia]], which makes his exceptionally rare hugs extremely awkward and painful-looking. He also has [[hemophobia]].<ref>''[[The Big Bang Theory (season 5)|s5 e16, The Vacation Solution]]''</ref> Sheldon has difficulty coping when asked to keep a secret, when he is interrupted, or when he hears arguing.<ref name=\"S02E01\">{{cite episode|title=The Bad Fish Paradigm|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=September 22, 2008|season=2|number=1}}</ref><ref name=\"S02E13\">{{cite episode|title=The Friendship Algorithm|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=January 19, 2009|season=2|number=13}}</ref><ref name=\"S03E07\">{{cite episode|title=The Guitarist Amplification|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=November 9, 2009|season=3|number=7}}</ref> He is also a [[notary public]] and uses his knowledge in law and contracts usually for his own advantage and is always distressed when challenged in a legal aspect that he cannot logically defend. In his mannerisms, Sheldon also shows symptoms associated with [[obsessive-compulsive personality disorder]]. Whenever approaching a person's home, he must knock three times, then say the person's name, and must repeat this at least three times (where \"The first one is traditional, but two and three are for people to get their pants on\"), as a result of him walking in on his father with another woman when he was thirteen.<ref name=\"S10E05\">{{cite episode|title=The Hot Tub Contamination|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=October 16, 2016|season=10|number=5}}</ref> Upon entering a person's home, he must select the proper seat before sitting down. When it was suggested by Penny that he \"just sit anywhere\", his response is \"Oh, no, if only it were that simple!\" Because of his rigidity and stubbornness, only his mother and Bernadette,<ref name=\"S03E14\">{{cite episode|title=[[The Big Bang Theory (season 3)#ep14|The Einstein Approximation]]|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=February 1, 2010|season=3|number=14}}</ref> both possessing strong maternal personalities, have shown the ability to order him to do things.\n{{anchor|interests}}\nLike his friends, Sheldon is fond of comic books (especially the [[DC Universe]]), [[Cosplay|costumes]], [[video game]]s (he also mentions his ownership of various [[Retrogaming|vintage games and systems]]), [[roleplaying game]]s, [[tabletop game]]s, [[collectible card game]]s, and action figures. Sheldon has [[restraining orders]] from his heroes [[Leonard Nimoy]], [[Carl Sagan]], and [[Stan Lee]],<ref name=\"S03E15\">{{cite episode|title=The Large Hadron Collision|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=February 8, 2010|season=3|number=15}}</ref><ref name=\"S03E16\">{{cite episode|title=The Excelsior Acquisition|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=March 1, 2010|season=3|number=16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode|title=The Vacation Solution|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 5)#ep103|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=February 9, 2012|season=5|number=16|minutes=12:55}}</ref><ref name=S02E11>Season 2, episode 11: The Bath Item Gift Hypothesis</ref> as well as television scientist [[Bill Nye]].<ref name=S07E7>{{cite episode|title=The Proton Displacement|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 7)#ep142|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=November 7, 2013|season=7|number=7|minutes=16:23}}</ref> Sheldon often wears vintage T-shirts adorned with superhero logos.  One of his shirts is emblazoned with the number [[73 (number)|73]], and in the episode \"The Alien Parasite Hypothesis\" he explains that 73 is the 21st prime number, its mirror, 37, is the 12th prime number and its mirror (21) is the product of multiplying 7 and 3, also in binary, 73 is 1001001, a [[palindrome]]. The boys use video games like bowling and archery for \"exercise\" and use the traditional sport rules.\n\nSheldon has sometimes shown empathy, including lending money to [[Penny (The Big Bang Theory)|Penny]] without expecting it back quickly (although that may just have been his logical [[Spock]]-like response to a problem to be solved; it was, after all, money he was not using and would not miss<ref name=\"S02E14\">{{cite episode|title=The Financial Permeability|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=February 2, 2009|season=2|number=14}}</ref>) and driving her to a hospital when her shoulder was dislocated.<ref name=\"S03E8\">{{cite episode|title=The Adhesive Duck Deficiency|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=November 16, 2009|season=3|number=9}}</ref> Since season 10, his empathy and caring attitude toward others have improved to the extent that he goes out of his way to pamper his fianc\u00e9e Amy. Sheldon admits he is overly fond of koalas munching on eucalyptus so much that he has a facial expression that he refers to as his koala face.<ref>\"The Tiny Trinket Maneuver\". ''The Big Bang Theory''. Season 5. episode 12. January 12, 2012. CBS.</ref> He dislikes gifts, because the \"social convention\" in his view creates either a debt or burden on the receiver of the gift which will not stop until one of the two involved in the \"gift-relationship\" dies leaving the other either in debt or with an undue surplus.<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Bath Item Gift Hypothesis|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=December 15, 2008|season=2|number=11}}</ref> Sheldon also does not take drugs, not even legal ones such as caffeine, due to a promise to his mother, and is hypersensitive when he accidentally consumes them.<ref name=\"S0218\">{{cite episode|title=The Work Song Nanocluster|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|season=2|number=18}}</ref><ref name=\"S02E01\"/> However, it has been shown that alcohol often causes Sheldon to loosen up significantly,<ref name=\"1x12\" /> although it will also cloud his judgment on occasion. After drinking alcoholic drinks (both deliberately and accidentally), he has done things that he would never do while sober, such as singing out loud,<ref name=\"S01E08\">{{cite episode|title=The Grasshopper Experiment|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=November 12, 2007|season=1|number=8}}</ref> mooning an audience full of people,<ref name=\"S03E18\"/> confronting [[Wil Wheaton]],<ref name=\"S06E07\">{{cite episode|title=The Habitation Configuration|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=November 8, 2012|season=6|number=7}}</ref> leaving wildly inappropriate voicemails after \"drunk dialling\" [[Stephen Hawking]], and affectionately slapping Amy's rear.<ref name=\"S07E09\">{{cite episode|title=The Thanksgiving Decoupling|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=November 21, 2013|season=7|number=9}}</ref>\n\nIn response to criticism from his friends that he is mentally ill, Sheldon often retorts, \"I'm not crazy; my mother had me tested\"; which his mother has confirmed to be true (once while wishing she had gone through with a follow-up examination).<ref name=\"S02E16\">{{cite episode|title=The Cushion Saturation|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=March 2, 2009|season=2|number=16}}</ref><ref name=\"S02E04\">{{cite episode|title=The Griffin Equivalency|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=October 13, 2008|season=2|number=7}}</ref><ref name=\"S05E06\">{{cite episode|title=The Rhinitis Revelation|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=October 20, 2011|season=5|number=6}}</ref>\n\nIn the last two seasons, Sheldon begins to divert from his original personality. In the last episode, Sheldon went through a major change in personality.\n\n=== Family ===\nSheldon contrasts strongly with his family, who are neither scientists nor intellectuals. His father George died before the start of ''The Big Bang Theory'', when Sheldon was 14,<ref name=\"S07E22\">{{cite episode|title=The Proton Transmogrification|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=May 1, 2014|season=7|number=22}}</ref> while his mother Mary is a devout born-again Christian and loving parent. Sheldon has two siblings: a twin sister, Missy, who is a tall, attractive brunette as an adult; and an older brother,<ref name=\"S03E02\">{{cite episode|title=The Jiminy Conjecture|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=April 27, 2009|season=3|number=2}}</ref> George Jr., who owns a [[tire]] store chain headquartered in [[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]] called Dr. Tire.<ref name=\"S11E23\">{{cite episode|title=The Sibling Realignment|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=May 3, 2018|season=11|number=23}}</ref> The adult Sheldon has stated that both Missy and George Jr. beat up Sheldon during their childhoods, and their mother describes them to be \"dumb as soup\".<ref name=\"S01E04\">{{cite episode|title=The Luminous Fish Effect|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 1)#ep4|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=October 15, 2007|season=1|number=4}}</ref>  In the pilot episode of ''The Big Bang Theory'', Sheldon tells Leonard that DNA is not a guarantee of an intelligent offspring as he himself is a theoretical physicist and his twin sister is a hostess at [[Fuddruckers]]. Sheldon is very fond of his maternal grandmother, whom he calls \"Meemaw\" and who calls him \"[[Moon Pie]]\".<ref name=\"S02E17\">{{cite episode|title=The Terminator Decoupling|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=March 9, 2009|season=2|number=17}}</ref> He called his grandfather, who died when Sheldon was five, \"Pop Pop\".<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Santa Simulation|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 6)#ep11|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=December 13, 2012|season=6|number=11}}</ref> Sheldon was also very close to his grandfather, stating once that his grandfather is the only relative he had who encouraged him to become involved in science.\n\nSheldon has a maternal uncle, Edward, who is called \"Stumpy\" as the result of a time when he cleaned a wood chipper by hand. He also has a maternal aunt, Charlene, which was revealed in ''Young Sheldon'' when his mother told Meemaw that she made dinner for \u201cCharlene and Edward\u201d more times than her. Sheldon had another uncle, named Carl Cooper, who was killed by a badger while cleaning a chimney and another uncle that may have done things to children that were legal in Oklahoma per \"The Clean Room Infiltration\".\n\nIn \"The Engagement Reaction\", Sheldon mentions that his aunt Ruth died a week after being infected by a pathogen she contracted in the hospital where she visited Sheldon's uncle Roger, and that their ashes are now stored in a coffee can on Sheldon's mother's mantle. ''Young Sheldon'' confirms that Ruth is George's sister, and that she and Roger are still alive by 1990.\n\nIn the ''Young Sheldon'' episode \"Vanilla Ice Cream, Gentleman Callers, and a Dinette Set\", it is revealed that Sheldon has children in the future, but this is never referenced in ''The Big Bang Theory.''\n\n=== Relationships ===\nSheldon's closest friends are [[Leonard Hofstadter]], [[Howard Wolowitz]], and [[Raj Koothrappali]]. Of the three, Sheldon is openly dismissive of Howard and constantly [[wikt:opine|opines]] that a master's degree in engineering demonstrates a lesser intellect than that of the others, who all possess science doctorates. Despite that, Sheldon has referred to Howard as a \"treasured acquaintance\"<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Bozeman Reaction|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 3)#ep13|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=January 18, 2010|season=3|number=13}}</ref> and later his friend<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Friendship Turbulence|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 7)#ep17|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=March 6, 2014|season=7|number=17}}</ref> at various points. Sheldon constantly belittles Leonard and dismisses his work, yet at the same time considers Leonard his best friend, as they used to live together and can tolerate each other: in \"The Space Probe Disintegration\", Sheldon admits to Leonard that he is aware of how difficult he can be, and tearfully expresses his gratitude for having Leonard in his life in spite of himself, causing Leonard to break down beside him. Prady stated that \"the fact that, despite everything, Leonard considers Sheldon his best friend reminds us of Sheldon's essential humanity\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://featuresblogs.chicagotribune.com/entertainment_tv/2010/01/big-bang-theory-johnny-galecki-cbs-sheldon-leonard.html|title=Having 'Big' fun on a hit comedy: A chat with 'Big Bang Theory's' Johnny Galecki|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=January 10, 2010|accessdate=January 15, 2010}}</ref> Sheldon can only handle having a limited number of friends in his life at a time, but later shows flexibility when he accepts Bernadette and Amy as part of the social group. In season 6, the guys ask if comic book store owner Stuart can be part of the group while Howard is in space.<ref>The Decoupling Fluctuation, October 4, 2012.</ref>\n\nDespite Penny's neither being a scientist nor sharing many of the group's interests,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/106/1065246p2.html|title=Bazinga! Sheldon Speaks|work=[[IGN]]|date=January 29, 2010|accessdate=February 1, 2010}}</ref> and having constant fights with Sheldon in the early episodes, they become close friends.<ref name=\"S01E11\">{{cite episode|title=The Pancake Batter Anomaly|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 1)#ep11|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=March 31, 2008|season=1|number=11}}</ref> While some fans supported a romantic relationship between Sheldon and Penny,<ref name=\"LAT\">{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/dodgerthoughts/2009/12/big-bang-theory.html|title='The Big Bang Theory': Why Penny and Sheldon will hook up|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|author=Jon Weisman|date=December 8, 2009|accessdate=January 18, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091213013143/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/dodgerthoughts/2009/12/big-bang-theory.html|archivedate=December 13, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"EW3\">{{cite web|url=http://ausiellofiles.ew.com/2009/04/27/big-bang-video//|title='Big Bang' video: Jim Parsons tackles Sheldon-Penny romance, the virginity thing, and more!|work=The Ausiello Files|date=April 27, 2009|accessdate=January 13, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090926160414/http://ausiellofiles.ew.com/2009/04/27/big-bang-video/|archivedate=September 26, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Lorre stated his opposition to it by saying: \"We've stumbled into creating a character who has chosen a lifestyle for himself that is unique. And I don't see any reason to modify it.\"<ref name=\"EW1\">{{cite web|url=http://ausiellofiles.ew.com/2010/01/09/big-bang-scoop-romance-for-penny-and-sheldon/|title=Big Bang scoop: Romance for Penny and Sheldon?|work=[[IGN]]|date=January 9, 2010|accessdate=January 13, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114034133/http://ausiellofiles.ew.com/2010/01/09/big-bang-scoop-romance-for-penny-and-sheldon/|archivedate=January 14, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIt has been speculated that Sheldon may be [[Asexuality|asexual]] or [[aromantic]]. Series co-creator Chuck Lorre said: \"Part of what's wonderful and unique about [Sheldon] is he has chosen not to play in the relationship game either way&nbsp; \u2013 heterosexual, homosexual, bisexual, any sexuality.\"<ref name=\"EW1\"/> This is referenced in \"The Cooper-Nowitzki Theorem\", when Sheldon unknowingly attracts the attention of grad student Ramona Nowitzki, and Penny, seeing this, asks his friends what his \"deal\" (i.e., sexual orientation) is, to which Leonard responds, \"Honestly, we've been operating under the assumption that he has no 'deal'\".\n\n[[File:Mayim Bialik and Jim Parsons at PaleyFest 2013.jpg|thumb|[[Mayim Bialik]] (who portrays [[Amy Farrah Fowler]]) and Jim Parsons at PaleyFest 2013 for the TV show \"Big Bang Theory\"]]\nIn the [[The Big Bang Theory (season 3)#ep63|season 3 finale]], Howard and Raj blackmail Sheldon into meeting [[Amy Farrah Fowler]], with whom they matched him on a dating website. After some obnoxious comments about the dating website, Sheldon finds that Amy agrees with him, and he grows fond of her when she says that \"Any or all physical contact up to and including [[coitus]] are off the table\". Their relationship continues in season 4, although Sheldon often points out that they are not in a romantic relationship (stating that she \"is a girl who is a friend, but is not my girlfriend\"). The two enjoy intellectual games they create, and Amy and Sheldon openly express the same type of intellectual superiority.<ref name=\"S04E03\">{{cite episode|title=[[The Big Bang Theory (season 4)#ep3|The Zazzy Substitution]]|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=October 7, 2010|season=4|number=03}}</ref>\n\nIn season 5, when Leonard inadvertently implies that he and Amy may have had sex after a wedding reception that they both attended, Sheldon unexpectedly reacts violently, karate-chopping Leonard's neck while telling Leonard \"She is not for you... not for you!\"<ref name=\"S05E03\">{{cite episode|title=[[The Big Bang Theory (season 5)#ep3|The Pulled Groin Extrapolation]]|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=September 29, 2011|season=5|number=03}}</ref> Later, Sheldon formally asks Amy to be his girlfriend in \"[[The Flaming Spittoon Acquisition]]\". During their relationship, Amy begins a campaign to give Sheldon more attention to increase his feelings for her by embracing his interests.<ref name=\"S05E23\">{{cite episode|title=[[The Big Bang Theory (season 5)#ep3|The Launch Acceleration]]|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=May 3, 2012|season=5|number=23}}</ref> As they watch Howard being launched into space in its season finale, Amy is surprised when Sheldon takes her hand for emotional support.<ref name=\"S05E24\">{{cite episode|title=[[The Big Bang Theory (season 5)#ep3|The Countdown Reflection]]|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=May 10, 2012|season=5|number=24}}</ref>\n\nDuring the first half of season 6, in \"[[The Big Bang Theory (season 6)|The Parking Spot Escalation]]\" and \"[[The Fish Guts Displacement]]\", Sheldon is pushed further after seeing Amy partially exposed and taking care of her while she is ill respectively. In \"[[The Big Bang Theory (season 6)|The Cooper/Kripke Inversion]]\", after being directly asked by Penny if he would ever have sex with Amy, Sheldon admits to Penny and Leonard that a physical relationship with Amy is a possibility, and being touched is something he is working on. While upset about Kripke, Amy does give him a consoling hug that Sheldon seems to need, and want. Even so, Amy has offered other romantic physical contact, and was very uncomfortable when they had to cuddle. In \"[[The Big Bang Theory (season 6)|The Spoiler Alert Segmentation]]\", Leonard temporarily moves out and Amy proposes that she would be his perfect roommate and tries to move in, though Sheldon is uncomfortable with this change in their relationship. While playing Dungeons and Dragons during \"[[The Big Bang Theory (season 6)|The Love Spell Potential]]\", Sheldon's and Amy's characters are commanded to have sex within the game. A very upset Amy asks Sheldon if they are ever going to be intimate and he again admits that it is a possibility.\n\nIn season 7, Sheldon passionately kisses Amy on the lips for the first time. Initially to prove a point, he later prolonged it, implying he enjoyed the feeling.<ref>{{cite episode|title=[[The Big Bang Theory (season 7)#ep15|The Locomotive Manipulation]]|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=February 6, 2014|season=7|number=15}}</ref> Later episodes showed him willingly kissing Amy, implying he has gotten more comfortable in such a position of physical intimacy. The ultimate proof of Sheldon having feelings for Amy is given in the season 8 episode \"[[The Big Bang Theory (season 8)|The Prom Equivalency]]\", when he finally admits being in love with her: \"I love you too. There's no denying I have feelings for you that can't be explained in any other way. I briefly considered I had a brain parasite, but that seems even more far-fetched. The only conclusion was love.\" In the season 8 finale, \"[[The Big Bang Theory (season 8)|The Commitment Determination]]\", Sheldon and Amy get into a fight over their definition of \"commitment\".  Sheldon feels his relationship with Amy is going fast on its own, but Amy argues he is taking things too slowly and does not properly bestow on her unlimited affection. By the episode's end she has decided to take a break from their relationship while Sheldon is left numb from Amy's revelation. He glumly reveals that he had been planning on proposing to Amy with his grandmother's ring, a family heirloom.\n\nIn the season 9 premiere, Sheldon keeps pushing Amy to make up her mind about their relationship, but goes too far and insults her to her face and she angrily breaks up with him for good, thus officially ending their relationship. In \"[[The Big Bang Theory (season 9)|The Platonic Permutation]]\" Amy offers Sheldon to get back together with her after spending time together in an aquarium at Thanksgiving, but sadly learns that he simply just wants to be her friend, with him revealing to her that \"I excel at many things, but getting over you wasn't one of them\". In \"[[The Big Bang Theory (season 9)|The Earworm Reverberation]]\", Sheldon can't get a [[Darlin' (The Beach Boys song)|song]] out his head, but after suddenly remembering the title and the lyrics, he realizes that the song was about Amy and that she changed his life for the better, which prompts him to go to her apartment to profess his love. He finds Amy on a date with Dave, who has a great adoration for Sheldon because of his intellect. Seeing how much they love each other, Dave gleefully urges Sheldon to kiss Amy, leading to their reunion. In the following episode, \"[[The Big Bang Theory (season 9)|The Opening Night Excitation]]\" Leonard, Howard and Raj go to see ''[[Star Wars: The Force Awakens]]'' without Sheldon as while he was initially reluctant, ultimately opted to celebrate Amy's birthday with her instead. To make Amy's birthday enjoyable and memorable, Sheldon seeks out Penny and Bernadette as he respects their opinions regarding all things socially appropriate.  He reveals to them that he has narrowed things down to three options, the first being a chance to play the [[harp]] with the [[Los Angeles Philharmonic]], the second being an all-expense-paid trip to the Wisconsin Sheep and Wool Festival (though Amy would have to go alone because Sheldon's [[ornithophobia]] is nothing compared to his fear of sheep), and the third being the two of them engaging in [[coitus]], at which point Penny squeezes and shatters the wine glass in her hand due to disbelief and/or shock. After Penny and Bernadette convince him that finally being intimate with her is the most beautiful gift that he could give to her, Sheldon and Amy have sex for the first time on the latter's birthday.\n\nIn season 10, Sheldon and Amy move in together for a five-week experiment to test out their compatibility,<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Cohabitation Experimentation|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 10)#ep4|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=October 10, 2016|season=10|number=4}}</ref> and after its successful run, decide to move in together permanently.<ref name=\"The Veracity Elasticity\"/> In its season finale, Sheldon unexpectedly proposes to Amy after being hit on by Ramona Nowitzki. In the eleventh-season premiere, Amy accepts his proposal, and they marry in the season finale.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mondaymondaynetwork.com/entertainment/the-big-bang-theory/these-behind-the-scenes-big-bang-theory-wedding-details-will-shock-you/|title=These Behind The Scenes Big Bang Theory Details Will SHOCK You|last=|first=|date=2018-05-28|work=MondayMondayNetwork.com|access-date=2018-06-09|language=en-US}}</ref> Late in season 12, Amy is preparing Sheldon to accept them having children by getting him to have fun experimenting with the Wolowitz children. In [[The Big Bang Theory (season 12)|the series finale]], both Sheldon and Amy are recipients of the [[Nobel Prize in physics]] for their discovery of super asymmetry which they first worked on moments before their wedding. In Amy's speech, she encourages young girls around the world to study whatever they want. Instead of giving a self-centered speech, Sheldon [[The_Big_Bang_Theory_(season_12)#speech|thanks]] his family, his friends and his wife Amy for always supporting him.\n\nHe once idolized fictional prodigy [[Wesley Crusher]] from ''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation]]'', portrayed by Wil Wheaton, until Wheaton did not show up at a convention attended by Sheldon in 1995. Sheldon had spent 15 hours on a bus travelling to the convention during which time he was forced to break his rule about urinating in a moving vehicle. After this moment Wil Wheaton became number six on Sheldon's mortal enemy list (a list he started when he was 9 on a 5\u00bc-inch [[floppy disk]]). Wheaton was one of Sheldon's mortal enemies, along with his coworkers [[Barry Kripke]] and [[Leslie Winkle]]. Later, Wheaton managed to patch things up with Sheldon, only to inadvertently pass the enemy list spot to [[Brent Spiner]].<ref name=S05E05>{{cite episode|title=The Russian Rocket Reaction|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 5)#ep5|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=October 13, 2011|season=5|number=5|minutes=}}</ref> Sheldon would later resume his enmity with Wheaton in season 11's \"The Proton Regeneration\" when they compete for the lead role in an Internet reboot of Sheldon's childhood favorite science TV series, ''Professor Proton'', and Wheaton gets the part; however, when he sees how well Wheaton plays the role and on the advice of Howard, he apologizes to him.\n\n== Reception and legacy ==\n=== General ===\n[[File:\u0414\u0432\u0443\u0445\u0441\u043b\u043e\u0439\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0442.jpg|thumb|Sheldon Cooper doing the [[Vulcan salute]], stencil graffiti on a wall in [[Volgograd]], [[Russia]]]]\nBoth the character and Parsons' portrayal have received widespread acclaim, and is often cited as the main reason for the program's success by critics and fans alike.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/entertainment/the_tab/the_buzz-39481582.html|title=The buzz: Jim Parsons as Sheldon|last=Oswald|first=Brad|work=[[Winnipeg Free Press]]|accessdate=January 13, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100313081930/http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/entertainment/the_tab/the_buzz-39481582.html|archivedate=March 13, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/Entertainment/Television/article/575764|title=Nerd herd doing a bang-up job|last=Salem|first=Rob|date=January 24, 2009|work=The Toronto Star|accessdate=January 13, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.boston.com/ae/tv/articles/2009/02/08/gentle_twists_on_reliable_formulas_keep_viewers_hooked/|title=Gentle twists on reliable formulas keep viewers hooked|last=Gilbert|first=Matthew|date=February 8, 2009|work=The Boston Globe|accessdate=January 13, 2010}}</ref> James Chamberlin of IGN wrote: \"It's hard to imagine what ''The Big Bang Theory'' would be if it weren't for Jim Parsons' great portrayal of Sheldon Cooper\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/946/946275p1.html|title=\"The Friendship Algorithm\" Review|work=[[IGN]]|date=January 20, 2009|accessdate=January 13, 2010}}</ref> Matt Roush of ''[[TV Guide]]'' stated that \"there's a spark of divine inspiration in Jim Parsons' uproarious Sheldon Cooper\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguidemagazine.com/matt-roush-daily-review/what-a-year-3521.html|title=What a Year!|work=[[TV Guide]]|date=December 14, 2009|accessdate=January 13, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100218155304/http://www.tvguidemagazine.com/matt-roush-daily-review/what-a-year-3521.html|archivedate=February 18, 2010}}</ref> Ken Tucker of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' wrote that: \"Parsons is doing something rare on network TV: making intellectualism admirable, even heroic\".<ref name=\"EW2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20237937,00.html|title=The Big Bang Theory|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=November 5, 2008|accessdate=January 13, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn July 16, 2009, Parsons was nominated for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Comedy Series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cdn.emmys.tv/awards/2009ptemmys/61stemmys_noms.php|title=61st Primetime Emmy\u00ae Awards &#124; Academy of Television Arts & Sciences|publisher=Cdn.emmys.tv|date=July 19, 2012|accessdate=July 27, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091106152818/http://cdn.emmys.tv/awards/2009ptemmys/61stemmys_nomswin_pt.php?action=search_db#1|archivedate=November 6, 2009}}</ref> He was nominated again for the same award on July 8, 2010, and eventually won the award on August 29, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/sites/emmys.com/files/62ndemmys_noms.pdf|title=Complete Emmy listings|accessdate=July 8, 2010|publisher=Emmy Award|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111215131620/http://www.emmys.com/sites/emmys.com/files/62ndemmys_noms.pdf|archive-date=December 15, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On August 1, 2009, he won the [[TCA Award for Individual Achievement in Comedy]], with the show itself winning the award for [[TCA Award for Outstanding Achievement in Comedy|Outstanding Achievement in Comedy]] for season 2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://goldderby.latimes.com/awards_goldderby/2009/08/tca-awards-television-critics-association-news-.html|title=TCA Awards hail 'True Blood' and (finally) 'Battlestar Galactica'|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=August 2, 2009|accessdate=January 13, 2010}}</ref> He was nominated again for the same award in 2010 and 2012. Parsons was also nominated for the [[People's Choice Award]] for Favorite TV Comedy Actor<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peopleschoice.com/pca/awards/nominees/index.jsp|title=People's Choice Awards Nominees & Winners:2010|publisher=peoplschoice.com|accessdate=January 13, 2010}}</ref> and a [[Satellite Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy]] in 2009, 2010, and 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressacademy.com/satawards/awards2009.shtml|title=2009 14th Annual Satellite Awards|publisher=pressacademy.com|accessdate=January 13, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008032601/http://www.pressacademy.com/satawards/awards2009.shtml|archivedate=October 8, 2011}}</ref> On January 16, 2011, Parsons won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy]], presented by co-star [[Kaley Cuoco]], for his work on seasons 3 and 4. On June 20, 2011, he won the [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Actor in a Comedy Series]] at the [[1st Critics' Choice Television Awards]] for his work on season 4, and was nominated again for the same award in 2012. On September 18, 2011, he won his second consecutive [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Comedy Series|Primetime Emmy Award \u2013 Lead Actor in Comedy]], and was nominated again for the same award on July 19, 2012. In 2013, Parsons was nominated once again for the Golden Globe and received his first nomination for the [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Comedy Series]].  In 2013 and 2014, Parsons was nominated for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Comedy Series|Primetime Emmy Award \u2013 Lead Actor in Comedy]] for the 5th and 6th time, respectively, both of which he won for his 3rd and 4th [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Comedy Series|Primetime Emmy Awards \u2013 Lead Actor in a Comedy Series]] meaning that Parsons had won this award 4 times in the last 5 years, including back-to-back in 2010/2011and 2013/2014.  No actor, in the history of this award has won back-to-back awards on two separate occasions, and his total of 4 awards puts Parsons in a four-way tie at the top with comedy legends [[Carroll O'Connor]], [[Kelsey Grammer]], and [[Michael J. Fox]].\n\nThe asteroid [[List of minor planets: 246001\u2013247000#246201\u2013246300|246247 Sheldoncooper]] was named after Sheldon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=246247;orb=0;cov=0;log=0;cad=0#discovery|title=JPL Small-Body Database|accessdate=September 1, 2012}}</ref> In 2012, a newly discovered species of bee was named ''[[Euglossa bazinga]]'', after the character's noted [[catch phrase]], \"Bazinga!\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.smithsonianmag.com/smartnews/2012/12/a-brand-new-bee-was-just-named-after-sheldon-from-the-big-bang-theory|title=A Brand New Bee Was Just Named After Sheldon From 'The Big Bang Theory'|first=Rose|last=Eveleth|date=December 17, 2012|publisher=Smithsonion.com|agency=Smart News|accessdate=May 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2013, the [[Columbus Zoo and Aquarium]] named a [[black-and-white colobus]] after Sheldon.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.3news.co.nz/Zoo-names-monkey-after-TV-character/tabid/418/articleID/295533/Default.aspx|work=3 News NZ|title= Zoo names monkey after TV character| date=April 25, 2013}}</ref> In 2015, a new echinocaridid phyllocaridan from the Lower Devonian of central-eastern Poland, was named ''Ptychocaris sheldoni'' after Sheldon.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mazurek|first=Dawid|last2=Dec|first2=Marek|last3=\u0141ukowiak|first3=Magdalena|date=2015-11-01|title=A New Echinocaridid Phyllocaridan from the Lower Devonian of Central-Eastern Poland|journal=Journal of Crustacean Biology|volume=35|issue=6|pages=785\u2013788|doi=10.1163/1937240x-00002384|issn=0278-0372|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n=== Asperger syndrome ===\nSome viewers have asserted that Sheldon's behavior is consistent with [[Asperger syndrome]].<ref name=\"av\"/><ref name=SA /><ref name=\"slate\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Soraya|first=Lynne|title=Sheldony or Aspergery?: The Big Bang Theory|url=http://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/aspergers-diary/200904/sheldony-or-aspergery-the-big-bang-theory|work=Asperger's Diary (Author's Note (08/16/2009))|publisher=Psychology Today|accessdate=April 16, 2012}}</ref> The writers have stated that they did not use Asperger syndrome as a basis for the character, but instead thought of his actions as \"Sheldony\".<ref name=\"slate\">{{cite news|last=Collins|first=Paul|title=Must-Geek TV: Is the world ready for an Asperger's sitcom?|work=Slate|publisher=www.slate.com|date=February 6, 2009|url=http://www.slate.com/id/2210635/pagenum/all/#p2|accessdate=April 14, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210061649/http://www.slate.com/id/2210635/pagenum/all/|archivedate=February 10, 2009}}</ref> Series co-creator Bill Prady stated: \"We write the character as the character. A lot of people see various things in him and make the connections. Our feeling is that Sheldon's mother never got a diagnosis, so we don't have one.\"<ref name=\"squad\"/> Prady also told Alan Sepinwall of the New Jersey ''[[Star-Ledger]]'' that while Sheldon shares traits with people with Asperger's, he was uncomfortable labeling Sheldon as having Asperger's.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sepinwall|first=Alan|title=Does Sheldon from 'Big Bang Theory' have Asperger's?|url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/tv/index.ssf/2009/08/reader_mail_does_sheldon_from.html|publisher=The Star-Ledger|date=August 13, 2009|accessdate=July 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview, Jim Parsons noted the writers' response, but added that, in his opinion, Sheldon \"couldn't display ''more'' traits\" of Asperger's.<ref name=\"slate\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Lyford|first=Kathy|title='Big Bang Theory': Jim Parsons \u2013 'Everybody has a little Sheldon in them'|work=Season Pass|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=November 13, 2008|url=http://weblogs.variety.com/season_pass/2008/11/big-bang-theory.html|accessdate=April 14, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120722163909/http://weblogs.variety.com/season_pass/2008/11/big-bang-theory.html|archivedate=July 22, 2012|df=mdy-all}} Specific video is [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tOH2XD7KEeY Jim Parsons interview, part 5]. Question is from 03:18\u20133:31. Answer is from 4:36\u20136:00. Specific quote is from 5:15\u20135:20.</ref> Parsons, who plays Sheldon, has read [[John Elder Robison]]'s memoir ''[[Look Me in the Eye]]'' about his life with Asperger syndrome, and said that: \"A majority of what I read in that book touched on aspects of Sheldon.\" He also stated that \"the way his brain works, it's so focused on the intellectual topics at hand that thinking he's autistic is an easy leap for people watching the show to make\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.avclub.com/articles/jim-parsons,27415/|title=Jim Parsons|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=May 1, 2009|accessdate=January 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\nWhen another actor on the series, [[Mayim Bialik]], who plays Amy and has a Ph.D. in Neuroscience, was interviewed by [[Neil deGrasse Tyson]] on ''[[StarTalk (podcast)|StarTalk]]'', she said of the theory that Sheldon has Asperger's:\n<blockquote>All of our characters are in theory on the neuropsychiatric spectrum, I would say. Sheldon often gets talked about in terms of Asperger\u2019s or OCD. He has a thing with germs, he has a thing with numbers, he\u2019s got a lot of that precision that we see in OCD. There\u2019s a lot of interesting features to all of our characters that make them technically unconventional socially.... And what we\u2019re trying to show with our show is that this is a group of people who likely were teased, mocked, told that they will never be appreciated or loved, and we have a group of people who have successful careers, active social lives (that involve things like Dungeons and Dragons and video games), but they also have relationships, and that\u2019s a fulfilling and satisfying life.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gill|first=Jim|title='Is Sheldon autistic? The Big Bang Theory actress Mayim Bialik gives this brilliant response'|publisher=Immediate Media Company|date=15 June 2015|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-06-15/is-sheldon-autistic-the-big-bang-theory-actress-mayim-bialik-gives-this-brilliant-response/|accessdate=January 12, 2018}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Comedy|Television|Physics}}\n{{The Big Bang Theory}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cooper, Sheldon}}\n[[Category:Fictional characters from Texas]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters from Pasadena, California]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2007]]\n[[Category:Fictional child prodigies]]\n[[Category:Atheism in television]]\n[[Category:Fictional Nobel laureates]]\n[[Category:Fictional theoretical physicists]]\n[[Category:Fictional twins]]\n[[Category:The Big Bang Theory characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with eidetic memory]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters who became a protagonist in a spin-off]]\n[[Category:Child characters in television]]\n[[Category:Male characters in television]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Fictional theoretical physicist}}\n{{use American English|date=July 2013}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox character\n| color              = #AF181F\n| name               = Sheldon Lee Cooper\n| series             = [[The Big Bang Theory]]/[[Young Sheldon]]\n| image              = Sheldon and Young Sheldon.jpg\n| alt                = <!-- Include alt text per MOS:ALT. -->\n| caption            = Jim Parsons as adult Sheldon Cooper (left) and Iain Armitage as young Sheldon Cooper\n| first              = {{plainlist|\n* '''''The Big Bang Theory''''':\n* \"[[Pilot (The Big Bang Theory)|Pilot]]\" (2007)\n* '''''Young Sheldon''''':\n* \"[[Pilot (Young Sheldon)|Pilot]]\" (2017)\n}}\n| last               = {{plainlist|\n* '''''The Big Bang Theory''''':\n* \"[[The Stockholm Syndrome]]\" (2019)\n}}\n| creator            = [[Chuck Lorre]]<br>[[Bill Prady]]\n| portrayer          = [[Jim Parsons]]<br> (''[[The Big Bang Theory]]'')<br>[[Iain Armitage]] <br>(''[[Young Sheldon]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbs.com/shows/big_bang_theory/news/1006793/cbs-announces-young-sheldon-a-hilarious-spinoff-of-the-big-bang-theory/|title=Get Ready To Meet Young Sheldon, A Hilarious New Spinoff Of The Big Bang Theory - CBS.com}}</ref>\n| voice              = Jim Parsons <br>(Narration;<br> ''Young Sheldon'')\n| spouse             = [[Amy Farrah Fowler]]\n| children           = Unknown, other than that he has more than one (Mentioned by Jim Parsons in ''Young Sheldon'' narrations)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/amp/news/young-sheldon-baby-reveal/|title=Young Sheldon Revealed Something Huge About Sheldon's Future|publisher=TV Guide|date=May 10, 2018|accessdate=January 6, 2019}}</ref>\n| occupation         = {{plainlist|\n* '''''The Big Bang Theory''''':\n* [[Theoretical physicist]] \n* '''''Young Sheldon''''':\n* [[Student]] \n}}\n| full_name          = Sheldon Lee Cooper\n| title              = Doctor\n| family             = [[List of The Big Bang Theory characters#Mary Cooper|Mary Cooper]] (mother)<br>George Cooper Sr. (father, deceased as of ''Big Bang Theory'' timeline)<br>[[List of The Big Bang Theory characters#Missy Cooper|Missy Cooper]] (twin sister)<br>George \"Georgie\" Cooper Jr. (brother)<br>Missy's unnamed son (nephew)<br>Constance \"Connie\" Tucker/\"Meemaw\"<ref name=\"sheldonS1E17\">''[[Young Sheldon]]'' episode \"Jiu-Jitsu, Bubble Wrap, and Yoo-Hoo\"</ref> (maternal grandmother)<br>Charles \"Charlie\" Tucker/\"Pop Pop\" (maternal grandfather)\n| gender             = Male\n| nicknames          = Shelley, (family, friends) Shelley Bean, (mother) Moon Pie (grandmother)\n| nationality        = American\n| religion           = {{plainlist|\n* \"Mathology\" (his invention)\n}}\n}}\n'''<!-- Per  WP:CREDENTIAL, do not include \"Dr.\" or \"Doctor\" here. -->Sheldon Lee Cooper'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbs.com/shows/big_bang_theory/video/mwSWQujTYBsrVlLkz_Qimtolt3mBbJ5e/the-big-bang-theory-the-inspiration-deprivation/|title=The Inspiration Deprivation|date=Apr 18, 2019|website=CBS}}</ref><ref name=1x12>{{cite episode|title=The Jerusalem Duality|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 1)#ep12|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=April 14, 2008|season=1|number=12|minutes=}}</ref><!-- Do not add further credentials here. For a fuller explanation see Talk:Sheldon Cooper/Archive 1#Sheldon's postnominals --> [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]], [[Doctor of Science|Sc.D.]],<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Love Car Displacement|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 4)#ep76|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|airdate=January 20, 2011|season=4|number=13|minutes=16:39}}</ref> is a fictional character in the [[CBS]] television series ''[[The Big Bang Theory]]'' and its spinoff series ''[[Young Sheldon]]'', portrayed by actors [[Jim Parsons]] in ''The Big Bang Theory'' and [[Iain Armitage]] in ''Young Sheldon'' (with Parsons as the latter series' narrator).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/03/the-big-bang-theory-sheldon-spinoff-iain-armitage-zoe-perry-cast-1202034391/|title='Big Bang' Sheldon Spinoff Inches Closer With Iain Armitage & Zoe Perry Castings|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=March 2, 2017|accessdate=March 13, 2017}}</ref> For his portrayal, Parsons has won four [[Primetime Emmy Award]]s, a [[Golden Globe Award]], a [[TCA Awards|TCA Award]], and two [[Critics' Choice Television Award]]s. The character's childhood is the focus of ''Young Sheldon'': the series' first season is set in 1989 when nine-year-old [[child prodigy|prodigy]] Sheldon has skipped ahead five grades, to start high school alongside his older brother.\n\nThe adult Sheldon is a senior [[Theoretical physics|theoretical physicist]] at [[California Institute of Technology|The California Institute of Technology]] (Caltech), and for the first ten seasons of ''The Big Bang Theory'' shares an apartment with his colleague and best friend, [[Leonard Hofstadter]] ([[Johnny Galecki]]); they are also friends and coworkers with [[Howard Wolowitz]] ([[Simon Helberg]]) and [[Raj Koothrappali]] ([[Kunal Nayyar]]). In season 10, Sheldon moves across the hall with his girlfriend [[List of The Big Bang Theory characters#Amy|Amy]] ([[Mayim Bialik]]), in the former apartment of Leonard's wife [[Penny (The Big Bang Theory)|Penny]] ([[Kaley Cuoco]]).<ref name=\"The Veracity Elasticity\">{{cite episode|title=The Veracity Elasticity|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 10)#ep7|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=October 17, 2016|season=10|number=7}}</ref> He has a genius-level IQ, but displays a fundamental lack of [[social skills]], a tenuous understanding of humor, and difficulty recognizing [[irony]] and [[sarcasm]] in other people, although he himself often employs them. He exhibits highly idiosyncratic behavior and a general lack of [[humility]], [[empathy]], and [[toleration]]. These characteristics provide the majority of the humor involving him, which has caused him to be described as the show's [[breakout character]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/876/876616p1.html|title=The Big Bang Theory: Season 1 Review|work=[[IGN]]|date=May 27, 2007|access-date=January 13, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-01-11/entertainment/1001100121_1_big-bang-theory-audience-nerds|title=Oak Park native finally gets the girl in 'Big Bang'|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=January 11, 2010|accessdate=January 13, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"av\">{{cite web|url=https://www.avclub.com/articles/the-griffin-equivalency,13255/|title=The Griffin Equivalency|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=October 13, 2008|access-date=October 6, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"EW2\"/> Some viewers have asserted that Sheldon's personality is consistent with [[Asperger syndrome]] and [[obsessive\u2013compulsive disorder]].<ref name=\"av\"/><ref name=SA>{{cite web|last=Waldman|first=Allison|url=http://www.aoltv.com/2009/08/14/come-up-with-a-new-theory-sheldon-does-not-have-aspergers|title=Come up with a new theory: Sheldon does NOT have Asperger's|date=August 14, 2009|publisher=aoltv.com|accessdate=February 5, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120523181231/http://www.aoltv.com/2009/08/14/come-up-with-a-new-theory-sheldon-does-not-have-aspergers/|archivedate=May 23, 2012}}</ref> Co-creator [[Bill Prady]] has stated that Sheldon's character was neither conceived nor developed with regard to any of these traits,<ref name=SA/> although Parsons has said that in his opinion, Sheldon \"couldn't display ''more'' traits\" of Asperger's.\n\n== Creation and casting ==\nThe character of Sheldon Cooper was inspired by a computer programmer personally known to series co-creator Bill Prady.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thetvaddict.com/2009/04/17/paley-festival-recap-%E2%80%9809-the-big-bang-theory/|title=Paley Festival Recap '09: The Big Bang Theory|work=theTVaddict.com|date=April 17, 2009|accessdate=January 20, 2010}}</ref> He is named in honor of actor/producer [[Sheldon Leonard]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weblogs.variety.com/season_pass/2009/05/big-bang-theory-we-didnt-anticipate-how-protective-the-audience-would-feel-toward-our-guys.html|title='Big Bang Theory': 'We didn't anticipate how protective the audience would feel about our guys'|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=May 5, 2009|accessdate=February 5, 2010|quote=''Q. Are Sheldon and Leonard named after the brilliant (producer) Sheldon Leonard of \"The Andy Griffith Show\", \"The Danny Thomas Show\", \"The Dick Van Dyke Show\", \"My Favorite Martian\" and \"I Spy?\" (Binnie)'' A. Yep. Chuck and I are both fans. Chuck's idea.}}</ref> and Nobel Prize Laureate [[Leon Cooper]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vos.lavoz.com.ar/content/la-formula-perfecta-del-humor-0|title=The Big Bang Theory, la f\u00f3rmula perfecta del humor}}</ref> [[Chuck Lorre]] originally intended [[Johnny Galecki]] to play the role, but Galecki thought he would be \"better suited\" for the character of Leonard.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.collider.com/entertainment/interviews/article.asp/aid/11261/tcid/1|title=Johnny Galecki Exclusive Video Interview  \u2013 The Big Bang Theory|work=collider.com|date=March 15, 2009|accessdate=January 20, 2010}}</ref> Lorre said that when [[Jim Parsons]] auditioned for the role, he was \"so startlingly good\" that he was asked to reaudition \"to make sure he hadn't gotten lucky\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/arts/tv/features/59213/|title=The Science Guy|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|author=Emma Rosenblum|date=September 20, 2009|accessdate=January 20, 2010}}</ref> Sheldon is one of only four characters to appear in every episode of the series along with Leonard, Howard and Raj.\n\n==Characterization==\n\n=== Early life ===\nSheldon was raised in [[Galveston, Texas]]<ref name=\"S02E09\">{{cite episode|title=The White Asparagus Triangulation|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 2)#ep26|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=November 24, 2008|season=2|number=9|minutes=04:15}}</ref> along with his older brother, [[George Cooper, Jr.|George Jr.]], and [[Twin|fraternal twin]] sister, Missy, by his mother, Mary Cooper, an overtly devout Baptist; and his father, [[George Cooper, Sr.|George Cooper]], a football coach.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mondaymondaynetwork.com/entertainment/the-family-dynasty-part-1-sheldon-coopers-family/|title=The Family Dynasty \u2013 Part 1: Sheldon Cooper\u2019s Family|date=2016-11-16|work=MondayMondayNetwork.com|access-date=2018-06-09|language=en-US}}</ref> Sheldon once got his father fired when he told Mr. Hinckley, a store owner, that George was stealing from the cash register.<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Sales Call Sublimation|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 9)#ep12|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=January 7, 2015|season=9|number=12}}</ref> In ''Young Sheldon'', this is [[retcon]]ned: his father is a football coach who was fired from his coaching position in Galveston because he disclosed that other coaches were illegally recruiting players to their school, forcing the family to return to Medford, a fictional town in [[East Texas]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.texasmonthly.com/the-culture/young-sheldon/|title=Jim Parsons Returns With \u2018Young Sheldon\u2019|last=Kelly|first=Christopher|date=September 21, 2017|website=Texas Monthly|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200413105954/https://www.texasmonthly.com/the-culture/young-sheldon/|archive-date=April 13, 2020|access-date=April 13, 2020}}</ref> He does drink, mostly beer, but is a loving father who is trying to understand his intellectually gifted son. The only member of his family to have actively encouraged his work in science was his maternal grandfather, whom he cherished and affectionately called \"Pop-Pop\", and who died when Sheldon was five years old. Pop-Pop's loss is what caused Sheldon to despise Christmas when his Christmas wish to bring Pop-Pop back didn't come true. Sheldon's closest relative is his maternal grandmother whom he affectionately calls \"Meemaw\", and who in turn calls him \"Moon Pie\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mondaymondaynetwork.com/entertainment/family-dynasty-part-2-sheldon-coopers-family/|title=The Family Dynasty Part 2: Sheldon Cooper\u2019s Family|date=2016-11-16|work=MondayMondayNetwork.com|access-date=2018-06-09|language=en-US}}</ref> His aunt was also said to have encouraged his work in science by giving him medical equipment, \"in case his work in physics failed, he'd have a 'trade' to fall back on\".\n\nSheldon was interested in science from an early age, and was a [[child prodigy]],<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Creepy Candy Coating Corollary|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 3)#ep45|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=October 19, 2009|season=3|number=5}}</ref> although due to his behavioral quirks and his lack of humility about his superior intellect, he was bullied by classmates and neighbors. Sheldon entered college at the age of eleven,<ref name=\"S01E05\">{{cite episode|title=The Hamburger Postulate|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 1)#ep5|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=October 22, 2007|season=1|number=5}}</ref> and at age fourteen he graduated from college ''[[Latin honors|summa cum laude]]''.<ref name=\"S03E18\">{{cite episode|title=The Pants Alternative|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 3)#ep18|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=March 22, 2010|season=3|number=18}}</ref> For a long time, the college he went to for undergraduate studies had not been revealed, but he always felt it was superior to his fellow ''Big Bang Theory'' colleagues' alma maters of Princeton (Leonard), MIT (Howard) and Harvard (Amy); however, it is implied in \"The Tam Turbulence\" (Season 12, Episode 4) that Sheldon is in fact a Caltech alumnus. From then, he worked on his doctorate, was a visiting professor at the [[University of Heidelberg]] in Germany, was the youngest person at the time to receive the Stevenson Award,<ref name=1x12 /> and has appeared on the cover of ''[[Journal of Physical Chemistry A]]''.<ref name=\"S10E14\">{{cite episode|title=The Emotion Detection Automation|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 10)#ep14|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=February 7, 2017|season=10|number=14}}</ref> Sheldon is now a theoretical physicist doing research at [[Caltech]], although he stated in ''Young Sheldon'' that he couldn't see himself living in California due to their carefree lifestyle.\n\n=== Personality ===\n{{redirect|Bazinga|the jellyfish genus|Bazinga (genus)|the YouTuber|Behzinga}}\nLike Leonard, Raj, and Howard, Sheldon is characterized as being highly intelligent, but he tends to display childish qualities, such as extreme stubbornness, meanness, and a lack of [[common sense]]. It is claimed by Bernadette that the reason Sheldon is sometimes mean is because the part of his brain that tells him it is wrong to be mean is \"getting a [[wedgie]] from the rest of his brain\".<ref>''[[The Big Bang Theory (season 5)|s5 e21, The Hawking Excitation]]''</ref> Although, in season 8's \"The Space Probe Disintegration\",<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mondaymondaynetwork.com/entertainment/big-bang-theory-sheldon-bloopers/|title=The Big Bang Theory Sheldon Bloopers|date=2018-01-28|work=MondayMondayNetwork.com|access-date=2018-06-09|language=en-US}}</ref> Sheldon tearfully admits to Leonard that he ''is'' aware of his peculiarities and how his behavior comes across. The first four episodes of ''The Big Bang Theory'' portray Sheldon slightly inconsistently with respect to his later characterization, in which he is depicted as rather witty and sarcastic, and slightly flirtatious towards Penny in the pilot episode: according to Prady, the character \"began to evolve after episode five or so and became his own thing\".<ref name=\"squad\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvsquad.com/2009/08/14/come-up-with-a-new-theory-sheldon-does-not-have-aspergers|title=Come up with a new theory: Sheldon does NOT have Asperger's|publisher=[[TV Squad]]|date=August 14, 2009|accessdate=October 6, 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090817125113/http://www.tvsquad.com/2009/08/14/come-up-with-a-new-theory-sheldon-does-not-have-aspergers|archivedate=August 17, 2009}}</ref>\n\nSheldon possesses an [[eidetic memory]] and an IQ of 187,<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Pancake Batter Anomaly|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 1)#ep11|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=March 31, 2008|season=1|number=11|minutes=09:58|quote=Penny, I have an IQ of 187}}</ref> although he claims his IQ cannot be accurately measured by normal tests.<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Codpiece Topology|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 2)#ep19|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=September 29, 2008|season=2|number=2|minutes=08:20}}</ref> He originally claimed to have a master's degree and two [[Doctorate|doctoral degrees]], but this list has increased.<ref name=S01E02>{{cite episode|title=The Big Bran Hypothesis|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 1)#ep2|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=October 1, 2007|season=1|number=2|minutes=16:00}}</ref><ref name=S04E01>{{cite episode|title=The Robotic Manipulation|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 4)#ep64|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=September 23, 2010|season=4|number=1|minutes=09:36}}</ref> Sheldon has an extensive general knowledge in many subjects including physics, chemistry, biology, astronomy, [[cosmology]], algebra, calculus, economics, computers, [[vexillology]], engineering, history, geography, linguistics, programming in [[Java (programming language)|Java]], geology (although he mostly despises it and geologists \u2013 it is revealed early in ''Young Sheldon'' that this might have more to do with an unfortunate incident with an older female classmate than any fault of the subject), [[American football]], trains, and in addition to being fluent in [[Klingon language|Klingon]], has some knowledge of Swedish,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbs.com/shows/big_bang_theory/video/mwSWQujTYBsrVlLkz_Qimtolt3mBbJ5e/the-big-bang-theory-the-inspiration-deprivation/|title=Watch The Big Bang Theory Season 12 Episode 19: The Inspiration Deprivation - Full show on CBS All Access|website=www.cbs.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-20}}</ref> Finnish, Hindi and Mandarin.<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Creepy Candy Coating Corollary|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 3)#ep5|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=October 19, 2009|season=3|number=5|minutes=13:55}}</ref> It is also revealed in ''Young Sheldon'' that he is proficient in [[Spanish language|Spanish]]. He also shows great talent in music, knowing how to play the piano (as does Parsons in real life), the bongos, the [[Recorder (musical instrument)|recorder]], [[theremin]] (which Parsons learned to play in real life), shows some skill in [[Tuvan throat singing]] and also has perfect pitch.<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Bon Voyage Reaction|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 6)#ep24|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=May 16, 2013|season=6|number=24}}</ref>  Although his friends have similar intellects to him, his eccentricities, stubbornness, and large ego (Sheldon frequently points out his superiority on a daily basis and does not treat anyone as his equal, implying he suffers from [[narcissistic personality disorder]]) frequently frustrate them. Sheldon occasionally uses slang (in a very unnatural fashion) and follows jokes with his [[catchphrase]] \"Bazinga!\", which is now an officially registered trademark of [[Warner Bros.]]<ref name=trademarkia>{{cite web|title=Bazinga!|author=Warner Bros. Entertainment Inc.|url=http://www.trademarkia.com/bazinga-85210353.html|accessdate=September 24, 2011}}</ref><ref name=USPTO>{{cite web|title=USPTO Trademark Status and Document Retrieval|url=http://tsdr.uspto.gov/#caseNumber=85210239&caseType=SERIAL_NO&searchType=statusSearch|accessdate=February 18, 2013}}</ref> He is uncomfortable with human physical contact and has [[Mysophobia|germophobia]], which makes his exceptionally rare hugs extremely awkward and painful-looking. He also has [[hemophobia]].<ref>''[[The Big Bang Theory (season 5)|s5 e16, The Vacation Solution]]''</ref> Sheldon has difficulty coping when asked to keep a secret, when he is interrupted, or when he hears arguing.<ref name=\"S02E01\">{{cite episode|title=The Bad Fish Paradigm|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=September 22, 2008|season=2|number=1}}</ref><ref name=\"S02E13\">{{cite episode|title=The Friendship Algorithm|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=January 19, 2009|season=2|number=13}}</ref><ref name=\"S03E07\">{{cite episode|title=The Guitarist Amplification|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=November 9, 2009|season=3|number=7}}</ref> He is also a [[notary public]] and uses his knowledge in law and contracts usually for his own advantage and is always distressed when challenged in a legal aspect that he cannot logically defend. In his mannerisms, Sheldon also shows symptoms associated with [[obsessive-compulsive personality disorder]]. Whenever approaching a person's home, he must knock three times, then say the person's name, and must repeat this at least three times (where \"The first one is traditional, but two and three are for people to get their pants on\"), as a result of him walking in on his father with another woman when he was thirteen.<ref name=\"S10E05\">{{cite episode|title=The Hot Tub Contamination|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=October 16, 2016|season=10|number=5}}</ref> Upon entering a person's home, he must select the proper seat before sitting down. When it was suggested by Penny that he \"just sit anywhere\", his response is \"Oh, no, if only it were that simple!\" Because of his rigidity and stubbornness, only his mother and Bernadette,<ref name=\"S03E14\">{{cite episode|title=[[The Big Bang Theory (season 3)#ep14|The Einstein Approximation]]|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=February 1, 2010|season=3|number=14}}</ref> both possessing strong maternal personalities, have shown the ability to order him to do things.\n{{anchor|interests}}\nLike his friends, Sheldon is fond of comic books (especially the [[DC Universe]]), [[Cosplay|costumes]], [[video game]]s (he also mentions his ownership of various [[Retrogaming|vintage games and systems]]), [[roleplaying game]]s, [[tabletop game]]s, [[collectible card game]]s, and action figures. Sheldon has [[restraining orders]] from his heroes [[Leonard Nimoy]], [[Carl Sagan]], and [[Stan Lee]],<ref name=\"S03E15\">{{cite episode|title=The Large Hadron Collision|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=February 8, 2010|season=3|number=15}}</ref><ref name=\"S03E16\">{{cite episode|title=The Excelsior Acquisition|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=March 1, 2010|season=3|number=16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite episode|title=The Vacation Solution|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 5)#ep103|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=February 9, 2012|season=5|number=16|minutes=12:55}}</ref><ref name=S02E11>Season 2, episode 11: The Bath Item Gift Hypothesis</ref> as well as television scientist [[Bill Nye]].<ref name=S07E7>{{cite episode|title=The Proton Displacement|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 7)#ep142|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=November 7, 2013|season=7|number=7|minutes=16:23}}</ref> Sheldon often wears vintage T-shirts adorned with superhero logos.  One of his shirts is emblazoned with the number [[73 (number)|73]], and in the episode \"The Alien Parasite Hypothesis\" he explains that 73 is the 21st prime number, its mirror, 37, is the 12th prime number and its mirror (21) is the product of multiplying 7 and 3, also in binary, 73 is 1001001, a [[palindrome]]. The boys use video games like bowling and archery for \"exercise\" and use the traditional sport rules.\n\nSheldon has sometimes shown empathy, including lending money to [[Penny (The Big Bang Theory)|Penny]] without expecting it back quickly (although that may just have been his logical [[Spock]]-like response to a problem to be solved; it was, after all, money he was not using and would not miss<ref name=\"S02E14\">{{cite episode|title=The Financial Permeability|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=February 2, 2009|season=2|number=14}}</ref>) and driving her to a hospital when her shoulder was dislocated.<ref name=\"S03E8\">{{cite episode|title=The Adhesive Duck Deficiency|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=November 16, 2009|season=3|number=9}}</ref> Since season 10, his empathy and caring attitude toward others have improved to the extent that he goes out of his way to pamper his fianc\u00e9e Amy. Sheldon admits he is overly fond of koalas munching on eucalyptus so much that he has a facial expression that he refers to as his koala face.<ref>\"The Tiny Trinket Maneuver\". ''The Big Bang Theory''. Season 5. episode 12. January 12, 2012. CBS.</ref> He dislikes gifts, because the \"social convention\" in his view creates either a debt or burden on the receiver of the gift which will not stop until one of the two involved in the \"gift-relationship\" dies leaving the other either in debt or with an undue surplus.<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Bath Item Gift Hypothesis|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=December 15, 2008|season=2|number=11}}</ref> Sheldon also does not take drugs, not even legal ones such as caffeine, due to a promise to his mother, and is hypersensitive when he accidentally consumes them.<ref name=\"S0218\">{{cite episode|title=The Work Song Nanocluster|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|season=2|number=18}}</ref><ref name=\"S02E01\"/> However, it has been shown that alcohol often causes Sheldon to loosen up significantly,<ref name=\"1x12\" /> although it will also cloud his judgment on occasion. After drinking alcoholic drinks (both deliberately and accidentally), he has done things that he would never do while sober, such as singing out loud,<ref name=\"S01E08\">{{cite episode|title=The Grasshopper Experiment|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=November 12, 2007|season=1|number=8}}</ref> mooning an audience full of people,<ref name=\"S03E18\"/> confronting [[Wil Wheaton]],<ref name=\"S06E07\">{{cite episode|title=The Habitation Configuration|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=November 8, 2012|season=6|number=7}}</ref> leaving wildly inappropriate voicemails after \"drunk dialling\" [[Stephen Hawking]], and affectionately slapping Amy's rear.<ref name=\"S07E09\">{{cite episode|title=The Thanksgiving Decoupling|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=November 21, 2013|season=7|number=9}}</ref>\n\nIn response to criticism from his friends that he is mentally ill, Sheldon often retorts, \"I'm not crazy; my mother had me tested\"; which his mother has confirmed to be true (once while wishing she had gone through with a follow-up examination).<ref name=\"S02E16\">{{cite episode|title=The Cushion Saturation|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=March 2, 2009|season=2|number=16}}</ref><ref name=\"S02E04\">{{cite episode|title=The Griffin Equivalency|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=October 13, 2008|season=2|number=7}}</ref><ref name=\"S05E06\">{{cite episode|title=The Rhinitis Revelation|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=October 20, 2011|season=5|number=6}}</ref>\n\nIn the last two seasons, Sheldon begins to divert from his original personality. In the last episode, Sheldon went through a major change in personality.\n\n=== Family ===\nSheldon contrasts strongly with his family, who are neither scientists nor intellectuals. His father George died before the start of ''The Big Bang Theory'', when Sheldon was 14,<ref name=\"S07E22\">{{cite episode|title=The Proton Transmogrification|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=May 1, 2014|season=7|number=22}}</ref> while his mother Mary is a devout born-again Christian and loving parent. Sheldon has two siblings: a twin sister, Missy, who is a tall, attractive brunette as an adult; and an older brother,<ref name=\"S03E02\">{{cite episode|title=The Jiminy Conjecture|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=April 27, 2009|season=3|number=2}}</ref> George Jr., who owns a [[tire]] store chain headquartered in [[Dallas, Texas|Dallas]] called Dr. Tire.<ref name=\"S11E23\">{{cite episode|title=The Sibling Realignment|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=May 3, 2018|season=11|number=23}}</ref> The adult Sheldon has stated that both Missy and George Jr. beat up Sheldon during their childhoods, and their mother describes them to be \"dumb as soup\".<ref name=\"S01E04\">{{cite episode|title=The Luminous Fish Effect|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 1)#ep4|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=October 15, 2007|season=1|number=4}}</ref>  In the pilot episode of ''The Big Bang Theory'', Sheldon tells Leonard that DNA is not a guarantee of an intelligent offspring as he himself is a theoretical physicist and his twin sister is a hostess at [[Fuddruckers]]. Sheldon is very fond of his maternal grandmother, whom he calls \"Meemaw\" and who calls him \"[[Moon Pie]]\".<ref name=\"S02E17\">{{cite episode|title=The Terminator Decoupling|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=March 9, 2009|season=2|number=17}}</ref> He called his grandfather, who died when Sheldon was five, \"Pop Pop\".<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Santa Simulation|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 6)#ep11|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=December 13, 2012|season=6|number=11}}</ref> Sheldon was also very close to his grandfather, stating once that his grandfather is the only relative he had who encouraged him to become involved in science.\n\nSheldon has a maternal uncle, Edward, who is called \"Stumpy\" as the result of a time when he cleaned a wood chipper by hand. He also has a maternal aunt, Charlene, which was revealed in ''Young Sheldon'' when his mother told Meemaw that she made dinner for \u201cCharlene and Edward\u201d more times than her. Sheldon had another uncle, named Carl Cooper, who was killed by a badger while cleaning a chimney and another uncle that may have done things to children that were legal in Oklahoma per \"The Clean Room Infiltration\".\n\nIn \"The Engagement Reaction\", Sheldon mentions that his aunt Ruth died a week after being infected by a pathogen she contracted in the hospital where she visited Sheldon's uncle Roger, and that their ashes are now stored in a coffee can on Sheldon's mother's mantle. ''Young Sheldon'' confirms that Ruth is George's sister, and that she and Roger are still alive by 1990.\n\nIn the ''Young Sheldon'' episode \"Vanilla Ice Cream, Gentleman Callers, and a Dinette Set\", it is revealed that Sheldon has children in the future, but this is never referenced in ''The Big Bang Theory.''\n\n=== Relationships ===\nSheldon's closest friends are [[Leonard Hofstadter]], [[Howard Wolowitz]], and [[Raj Koothrappali]]. Of the three, Sheldon is openly dismissive of Howard and constantly [[wikt:opine|opines]] that a master's degree in engineering demonstrates a lesser intellect than that of the others, who all possess science doctorates. Despite that, Sheldon has referred to Howard as a \"treasured acquaintance\"<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Bozeman Reaction|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 3)#ep13|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=January 18, 2010|season=3|number=13}}</ref> and later his friend<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Friendship Turbulence|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 7)#ep17|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=March 6, 2014|season=7|number=17}}</ref> at various points. Sheldon constantly belittles Leonard and dismisses his work, yet at the same time considers Leonard his best friend, as they used to live together and can tolerate each other: in \"The Space Probe Disintegration\", Sheldon admits to Leonard that he is aware of how difficult he can be, and tearfully expresses his gratitude for having Leonard in his life in spite of himself, causing Leonard to break down beside him. Prady stated that \"the fact that, despite everything, Leonard considers Sheldon his best friend reminds us of Sheldon's essential humanity\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://featuresblogs.chicagotribune.com/entertainment_tv/2010/01/big-bang-theory-johnny-galecki-cbs-sheldon-leonard.html|title=Having 'Big' fun on a hit comedy: A chat with 'Big Bang Theory's' Johnny Galecki|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=January 10, 2010|accessdate=January 15, 2010}}</ref> Sheldon can only handle having a limited number of friends in his life at a time, but later shows flexibility when he accepts Bernadette and Amy as part of the social group. In season 6, the guys ask if comic book store owner Stuart can be part of the group while Howard is in space.<ref>The Decoupling Fluctuation, October 4, 2012.</ref>\n\nDespite Penny's neither being a scientist nor sharing many of the group's interests,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/106/1065246p2.html|title=Bazinga! Sheldon Speaks|work=[[IGN]]|date=January 29, 2010|accessdate=February 1, 2010}}</ref> and having constant fights with Sheldon in the early episodes, they become close friends.<ref name=\"S01E11\">{{cite episode|title=The Pancake Batter Anomaly|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 1)#ep11|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=March 31, 2008|season=1|number=11}}</ref> While some fans supported a romantic relationship between Sheldon and Penny,<ref name=\"LAT\">{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/dodgerthoughts/2009/12/big-bang-theory.html|title='The Big Bang Theory': Why Penny and Sheldon will hook up|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|author=Jon Weisman|date=December 8, 2009|accessdate=January 18, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091213013143/http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/dodgerthoughts/2009/12/big-bang-theory.html|archivedate=December 13, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"EW3\">{{cite web|url=http://ausiellofiles.ew.com/2009/04/27/big-bang-video//|title='Big Bang' video: Jim Parsons tackles Sheldon-Penny romance, the virginity thing, and more!|work=The Ausiello Files|date=April 27, 2009|accessdate=January 13, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090926160414/http://ausiellofiles.ew.com/2009/04/27/big-bang-video/|archivedate=September 26, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Lorre stated his opposition to it by saying: \"We've stumbled into creating a character who has chosen a lifestyle for himself that is unique. And I don't see any reason to modify it.\"<ref name=\"EW1\">{{cite web|url=http://ausiellofiles.ew.com/2010/01/09/big-bang-scoop-romance-for-penny-and-sheldon/|title=Big Bang scoop: Romance for Penny and Sheldon?|work=[[IGN]]|date=January 9, 2010|accessdate=January 13, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114034133/http://ausiellofiles.ew.com/2010/01/09/big-bang-scoop-romance-for-penny-and-sheldon/|archivedate=January 14, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nIt has been speculated that Sheldon may be [[Asexuality|asexual]] or [[aromantic]]. Series co-creator Chuck Lorre said: \"Part of what's wonderful and unique about [Sheldon] is he has chosen not to play in the relationship game either way&nbsp; \u2013 heterosexual, homosexual, bisexual, any sexuality.\"<ref name=\"EW1\"/> This is referenced in \"The Cooper-Nowitzki Theorem\", when Sheldon unknowingly attracts the attention of grad student Ramona Nowitzki, and Penny, seeing this, asks his friends what his \"deal\" (i.e., sexual orientation) is, to which Leonard responds, \"Honestly, we've been operating under the assumption that he has no 'deal'\".\n\n[[File:Mayim Bialik and Jim Parsons at PaleyFest 2013.jpg|thumb|[[Mayim Bialik]] (who portrays [[Amy Farrah Fowler]]) and Jim Parsons at PaleyFest 2013 for the TV show \"Big Bang Theory\"]]\nIn the [[The Big Bang Theory (season 3)#ep63|season 3 finale]], Howard and Raj blackmail Sheldon into meeting [[Amy Farrah Fowler]], with whom they matched him on a dating website. After some obnoxious comments about the dating website, Sheldon finds that Amy agrees with him, and he grows fond of her when she says that \"Any or all physical contact up to and including [[coitus]] are off the table\". Their relationship continues in season 4, although Sheldon often points out that they are not in a romantic relationship (stating that she \"is a girl who is a friend, but is not my girlfriend\"). The two enjoy intellectual games they create, and Amy and Sheldon openly express the same type of intellectual superiority.<ref name=\"S04E03\">{{cite episode|title=[[The Big Bang Theory (season 4)#ep3|The Zazzy Substitution]]|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=October 7, 2010|season=4|number=03}}</ref>\n\nIn season 5, when Leonard inadvertently implies that he and Amy may have had sex after a wedding reception that they both attended, Sheldon unexpectedly reacts violently, karate-chopping Leonard's neck while telling Leonard \"She is not for you... not for you!\"<ref name=\"S05E03\">{{cite episode|title=[[The Big Bang Theory (season 5)#ep3|The Pulled Groin Extrapolation]]|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=September 29, 2011|season=5|number=03}}</ref> Later, Sheldon formally asks Amy to be his girlfriend in \"[[The Flaming Spittoon Acquisition]]\". During their relationship, Amy begins a campaign to give Sheldon more attention to increase his feelings for her by embracing his interests.<ref name=\"S05E23\">{{cite episode|title=[[The Big Bang Theory (season 5)#ep3|The Launch Acceleration]]|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=May 3, 2012|season=5|number=23}}</ref> As they watch Howard being launched into space in its season finale, Amy is surprised when Sheldon takes her hand for emotional support.<ref name=\"S05E24\">{{cite episode|title=[[The Big Bang Theory (season 5)#ep3|The Countdown Reflection]]|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=May 10, 2012|season=5|number=24}}</ref>\n\nDuring the first half of season 6, in \"[[The Big Bang Theory (season 6)|The Parking Spot Escalation]]\" and \"[[The Fish Guts Displacement]]\", Sheldon is pushed further after seeing Amy partially exposed and taking care of her while she is ill respectively. In \"[[The Big Bang Theory (season 6)|The Cooper/Kripke Inversion]]\", after being directly asked by Penny if he would ever have sex with Amy, Sheldon admits to Penny and Leonard that a physical relationship with Amy is a possibility, and being touched is something he is working on. While upset about Kripke, Amy does give him a consoling hug that Sheldon seems to need, and want. Even so, Amy has offered other romantic physical contact, and was very uncomfortable when they had to cuddle. In \"[[The Big Bang Theory (season 6)|The Spoiler Alert Segmentation]]\", Leonard temporarily moves out and Amy proposes that she would be his perfect roommate and tries to move in, though Sheldon is uncomfortable with this change in their relationship. While playing Dungeons and Dragons during \"[[The Big Bang Theory (season 6)|The Love Spell Potential]]\", Sheldon's and Amy's characters are commanded to have sex within the game. A very upset Amy asks Sheldon if they are ever going to be intimate and he again admits that it is a possibility.\n\nIn season 7, Sheldon passionately kisses Amy on the lips for the first time. Initially to prove a point, he later prolonged it, implying he enjoyed the feeling.<ref>{{cite episode|title=[[The Big Bang Theory (season 7)#ep15|The Locomotive Manipulation]]|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=February 6, 2014|season=7|number=15}}</ref> Later episodes showed him willingly kissing Amy, implying he has gotten more comfortable in such a position of physical intimacy. The ultimate proof of Sheldon having feelings for Amy is given in the season 8 episode \"[[The Big Bang Theory (season 8)|The Prom Equivalency]]\", when he finally admits being in love with her: \"I love you too. There's no denying I have feelings for you that can't be explained in any other way. I briefly considered I had a brain parasite, but that seems even more far-fetched. The only conclusion was love.\" In the season 8 finale, \"[[The Big Bang Theory (season 8)|The Commitment Determination]]\", Sheldon and Amy get into a fight over their definition of \"commitment\".  Sheldon feels his relationship with Amy is going fast on its own, but Amy argues he is taking things too slowly and does not properly bestow on her unlimited affection. By the episode's end she has decided to take a break from their relationship while Sheldon is left numb from Amy's revelation. He glumly reveals that he had been planning on proposing to Amy with his grandmother's ring, a family heirloom.\n\nIn the season 9 premiere, Sheldon keeps pushing Amy to make up her mind about their relationship, but goes too far and insults her to her face and she angrily breaks up with him for good, thus officially ending their relationship. In \"[[The Big Bang Theory (season 9)|The Platonic Permutation]]\" Amy offers Sheldon to get back together with her after spending time together in an aquarium at Thanksgiving, but sadly learns that he simply just wants to be her friend, with him revealing to her that \"I excel at many things, but getting over you wasn't one of them\". In \"[[The Big Bang Theory (season 9)|The Earworm Reverberation]]\", Sheldon can't get a [[Darlin' (The Beach Boys song)|song]] out his head, but after suddenly remembering the title and the lyrics, he realizes that the song was about Amy and that she changed his life for the better, which prompts him to go to her apartment to profess his love. He finds Amy on a date with Dave, who has a great adoration for Sheldon because of his intellect. Seeing how much they love each other, Dave gleefully urges Sheldon to kiss Amy, leading to their reunion. In the following episode, \"[[The Big Bang Theory (season 9)|The Opening Night Excitation]]\" Leonard, Howard and Raj go to see ''[[Star Wars: The Force Awakens]]'' without Sheldon as while he was initially reluctant, ultimately opted to celebrate Amy's birthday with her instead. To make Amy's birthday enjoyable and memorable, Sheldon seeks out Penny and Bernadette as he respects their opinions regarding all things socially appropriate.  He reveals to them that he has narrowed things down to three options, the first being a chance to play the [[harp]] with the [[Los Angeles Philharmonic]], the second being an all-expense-paid trip to the Wisconsin Sheep and Wool Festival (though Amy would have to go alone because Sheldon's [[ornithophobia]] is nothing compared to his fear of sheep), and the third being the two of them engaging in [[coitus]], at which point Penny squeezes and shatters the wine glass in her hand due to disbelief and/or shock. After Penny and Bernadette convince him that finally being intimate with her is the most beautiful gift that he could give to her, Sheldon and Amy have sex for the first time on the latter's birthday.\n\nIn season 10, Sheldon and Amy move in together for a five-week experiment to test out their compatibility,<ref>{{cite episode|title=The Cohabitation Experimentation|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 10)#ep4|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=October 10, 2016|season=10|number=4}}</ref> and after its successful run, decide to move in together permanently.<ref name=\"The Veracity Elasticity\"/> In its season finale, Sheldon unexpectedly proposes to Amy after being hit on by Ramona Nowitzki. In the eleventh-season premiere, Amy accepts his proposal, and they marry in the season finale.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mondaymondaynetwork.com/entertainment/the-big-bang-theory/these-behind-the-scenes-big-bang-theory-wedding-details-will-shock-you/|title=These Behind The Scenes Big Bang Theory Details Will SHOCK You|last=|first=|date=2018-05-28|work=MondayMondayNetwork.com|access-date=2018-06-09|language=en-US}}</ref> Late in season 12, Amy is preparing Sheldon to accept them having children by getting him to have fun experimenting with the Wolowitz children. In [[The Big Bang Theory (season 12)|the series finale]], both Sheldon and Amy are recipients of the [[Nobel Prize in physics]] for their discovery of super asymmetry which they first worked on moments before their wedding. In Amy's speech, she encourages young girls around the world to study whatever they want. Instead of giving a self-centered speech, Sheldon [[The_Big_Bang_Theory_(season_12)#speech|thanks]] his family, his friends and his wife Amy for always supporting him.\n\nHe once idolized fictional prodigy [[Wesley Crusher]] from ''[[Star Trek: The Next Generation]]'', portrayed by Wil Wheaton, until Wheaton did not show up at a convention attended by Sheldon in 1995. Sheldon had spent 15 hours on a bus travelling to the convention during which time he was forced to break his rule about urinating in a moving vehicle. After this moment Wil Wheaton became number six on Sheldon's mortal enemy list (a list he started when he was 9 on a 5\u00bc-inch [[floppy disk]]). Wheaton was one of Sheldon's mortal enemies, along with his coworkers [[Barry Kripke]] and [[Leslie Winkle]]. Later, Wheaton managed to patch things up with Sheldon, only to inadvertently pass the enemy list spot to [[Brent Spiner]].<ref name=S05E05>{{cite episode|title=The Russian Rocket Reaction|episodelink=The Big Bang Theory (season 5)#ep5|series=The Big Bang Theory|serieslink=The Big Bang Theory|network=[[CBS]]|date=October 13, 2011|season=5|number=5|minutes=}}</ref> Sheldon would later resume his enmity with Wheaton in season 11's \"The Proton Regeneration\" when they compete for the lead role in an Internet reboot of Sheldon's childhood favorite science TV series, ''Professor Proton'', and Wheaton gets the part; however, when he sees how well Wheaton plays the role and on the advice of Howard, he apologizes to him.\n\n== Reception and legacy ==\n=== General ===\n[[File:\u0414\u0432\u0443\u0445\u0441\u043b\u043e\u0439\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0442.jpg|thumb|Sheldon Cooper doing the [[Vulcan salute]], stencil graffiti on a wall in [[Volgograd]], [[Russia]]]]\nBoth the character and Parsons' portrayal have received widespread acclaim, and is often cited as the main reason for the program's success by critics and fans alike.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/entertainment/the_tab/the_buzz-39481582.html|title=The buzz: Jim Parsons as Sheldon|last=Oswald|first=Brad|work=[[Winnipeg Free Press]]|accessdate=January 13, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100313081930/http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/entertainment/the_tab/the_buzz-39481582.html|archivedate=March 13, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/Entertainment/Television/article/575764|title=Nerd herd doing a bang-up job|last=Salem|first=Rob|date=January 24, 2009|work=The Toronto Star|accessdate=January 13, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.boston.com/ae/tv/articles/2009/02/08/gentle_twists_on_reliable_formulas_keep_viewers_hooked/|title=Gentle twists on reliable formulas keep viewers hooked|last=Gilbert|first=Matthew|date=February 8, 2009|work=The Boston Globe|accessdate=January 13, 2010}}</ref> James Chamberlin of IGN wrote: \"It's hard to imagine what ''The Big Bang Theory'' would be if it weren't for Jim Parsons' great portrayal of Sheldon Cooper\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tv.ign.com/articles/946/946275p1.html|title=\"The Friendship Algorithm\" Review|work=[[IGN]]|date=January 20, 2009|accessdate=January 13, 2010}}</ref> Matt Roush of ''[[TV Guide]]'' stated that \"there's a spark of divine inspiration in Jim Parsons' uproarious Sheldon Cooper\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguidemagazine.com/matt-roush-daily-review/what-a-year-3521.html|title=What a Year!|work=[[TV Guide]]|date=December 14, 2009|accessdate=January 13, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100218155304/http://www.tvguidemagazine.com/matt-roush-daily-review/what-a-year-3521.html|archivedate=February 18, 2010}}</ref> Ken Tucker of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' wrote that: \"Parsons is doing something rare on network TV: making intellectualism admirable, even heroic\".<ref name=\"EW2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20237937,00.html|title=The Big Bang Theory|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=November 5, 2008|accessdate=January 13, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn July 16, 2009, Parsons was nominated for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Comedy Series]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cdn.emmys.tv/awards/2009ptemmys/61stemmys_noms.php|title=61st Primetime Emmy\u00ae Awards &#124; Academy of Television Arts & Sciences|publisher=Cdn.emmys.tv|date=July 19, 2012|accessdate=July 27, 2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091106152818/http://cdn.emmys.tv/awards/2009ptemmys/61stemmys_nomswin_pt.php?action=search_db#1|archivedate=November 6, 2009}}</ref> He was nominated again for the same award on July 8, 2010, and eventually won the award on August 29, 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/sites/emmys.com/files/62ndemmys_noms.pdf|title=Complete Emmy listings|accessdate=July 8, 2010|publisher=Emmy Award|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111215131620/http://www.emmys.com/sites/emmys.com/files/62ndemmys_noms.pdf|archive-date=December 15, 2011|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On August 1, 2009, he won the [[TCA Award for Individual Achievement in Comedy]], with the show itself winning the award for [[TCA Award for Outstanding Achievement in Comedy|Outstanding Achievement in Comedy]] for season 2.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://goldderby.latimes.com/awards_goldderby/2009/08/tca-awards-television-critics-association-news-.html|title=TCA Awards hail 'True Blood' and (finally) 'Battlestar Galactica'|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=August 2, 2009|accessdate=January 13, 2010}}</ref> He was nominated again for the same award in 2010 and 2012. Parsons was also nominated for the [[People's Choice Award]] for Favorite TV Comedy Actor<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.peopleschoice.com/pca/awards/nominees/index.jsp|title=People's Choice Awards Nominees & Winners:2010|publisher=peoplschoice.com|accessdate=January 13, 2010}}</ref> and a [[Satellite Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy]] in 2009, 2010, and 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pressacademy.com/satawards/awards2009.shtml|title=2009 14th Annual Satellite Awards|publisher=pressacademy.com|accessdate=January 13, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008032601/http://www.pressacademy.com/satawards/awards2009.shtml|archivedate=October 8, 2011}}</ref> On January 16, 2011, Parsons won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy]], presented by co-star [[Kaley Cuoco]], for his work on seasons 3 and 4. On June 20, 2011, he won the [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Actor in a Comedy Series]] at the [[1st Critics' Choice Television Awards]] for his work on season 4, and was nominated again for the same award in 2012. On September 18, 2011, he won his second consecutive [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Comedy Series|Primetime Emmy Award \u2013 Lead Actor in Comedy]], and was nominated again for the same award on July 19, 2012. In 2013, Parsons was nominated once again for the Golden Globe and received his first nomination for the [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Comedy Series]].  In 2013 and 2014, Parsons was nominated for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Comedy Series|Primetime Emmy Award \u2013 Lead Actor in Comedy]] for the 5th and 6th time, respectively, both of which he won for his 3rd and 4th [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Comedy Series|Primetime Emmy Awards \u2013 Lead Actor in a Comedy Series]] meaning that Parsons had won this award 4 times in the last 5 years, including back-to-back in 2010/2011and 2013/2014.  No actor, in the history of this award has won back-to-back awards on two separate occasions, and his total of 4 awards puts Parsons in a four-way tie at the top with comedy legends [[Carroll O'Connor]], [[Kelsey Grammer]], and [[Michael J. Fox]].\n\nThe asteroid [[List of minor planets: 246001\u2013247000#246201\u2013246300|246247 Sheldoncooper]] was named after Sheldon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=246247;orb=0;cov=0;log=0;cad=0#discovery|title=JPL Small-Body Database|accessdate=September 1, 2012}}</ref> In 2012, a newly discovered species of bee was named ''[[Euglossa bazinga]]'', after the character's noted [[catch phrase]], \"Bazinga!\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.smithsonianmag.com/smartnews/2012/12/a-brand-new-bee-was-just-named-after-sheldon-from-the-big-bang-theory|title=A Brand New Bee Was Just Named After Sheldon From 'The Big Bang Theory'|first=Rose|last=Eveleth|date=December 17, 2012|publisher=Smithsonion.com|agency=Smart News|accessdate=May 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2013, the [[Columbus Zoo and Aquarium]] named a [[black-and-white colobus]] after Sheldon.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.3news.co.nz/Zoo-names-monkey-after-TV-character/tabid/418/articleID/295533/Default.aspx|work=3 News NZ|title= Zoo names monkey after TV character| date=April 25, 2013}}</ref> In 2015, a new echinocaridid phyllocaridan from the Lower Devonian of central-eastern Poland, was named ''Ptychocaris sheldoni'' after Sheldon.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mazurek|first=Dawid|last2=Dec|first2=Marek|last3=\u0141ukowiak|first3=Magdalena|date=2015-11-01|title=A New Echinocaridid Phyllocaridan from the Lower Devonian of Central-Eastern Poland|journal=Journal of Crustacean Biology|volume=35|issue=6|pages=785\u2013788|doi=10.1163/1937240x-00002384|issn=0278-0372|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\n=== Asperger syndrome ===\nSome viewers have asserted that Sheldon's behavior is consistent with [[Asperger syndrome]].<ref name=\"av\"/><ref name=SA /><ref name=\"slate\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Soraya|first=Lynne|title=Sheldony or Aspergery?: The Big Bang Theory|url=http://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/aspergers-diary/200904/sheldony-or-aspergery-the-big-bang-theory|work=Asperger's Diary (Author's Note (08/16/2009))|publisher=Psychology Today|accessdate=April 16, 2012}}</ref> The writers have stated that they did not use Asperger syndrome as a basis for the character, but instead thought of his actions as \"Sheldony\".<ref name=\"slate\">{{cite news|last=Collins|first=Paul|title=Must-Geek TV: Is the world ready for an Asperger's sitcom?|work=Slate|publisher=www.slate.com|date=February 6, 2009|url=http://www.slate.com/id/2210635/pagenum/all/#p2|accessdate=April 14, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210061649/http://www.slate.com/id/2210635/pagenum/all/|archivedate=February 10, 2009}}</ref> Series co-creator Bill Prady stated: \"We write the character as the character. A lot of people see various things in him and make the connections. Our feeling is that Sheldon's mother never got a diagnosis, so we don't have one.\"<ref name=\"squad\"/> Prady also told Alan Sepinwall of the New Jersey ''[[Star-Ledger]]'' that while Sheldon shares traits with people with Asperger's, he was uncomfortable labeling Sheldon as having Asperger's.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sepinwall|first=Alan|title=Does Sheldon from 'Big Bang Theory' have Asperger's?|url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/tv/index.ssf/2009/08/reader_mail_does_sheldon_from.html|publisher=The Star-Ledger|date=August 13, 2009|accessdate=July 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview, Jim Parsons noted the writers' response, but added that, in his opinion, Sheldon \"couldn't display ''more'' traits\" of Asperger's.<ref name=\"slate\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Lyford|first=Kathy|title='Big Bang Theory': Jim Parsons \u2013 'Everybody has a little Sheldon in them'|work=Season Pass|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=November 13, 2008|url=http://weblogs.variety.com/season_pass/2008/11/big-bang-theory.html|accessdate=April 14, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120722163909/http://weblogs.variety.com/season_pass/2008/11/big-bang-theory.html|archivedate=July 22, 2012|df=mdy-all}} Specific video is [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tOH2XD7KEeY Jim Parsons interview, part 5]. Question is from 03:18\u20133:31. Answer is from 4:36\u20136:00. Specific quote is from 5:15\u20135:20.</ref> Parsons, who plays Sheldon, has read [[John Elder Robison]]'s memoir ''[[Look Me in the Eye]]'' about his life with Asperger syndrome, and said that: \"A majority of what I read in that book touched on aspects of Sheldon.\" He also stated that \"the way his brain works, it's so focused on the intellectual topics at hand that thinking he's autistic is an easy leap for people watching the show to make\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.avclub.com/articles/jim-parsons,27415/|title=Jim Parsons|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|date=May 1, 2009|accessdate=January 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\nWhen another actor on the series, [[Mayim Bialik]], who plays Amy and has a Ph.D. in Neuroscience, was interviewed by [[Neil deGrasse Tyson]] on ''[[StarTalk (podcast)|StarTalk]]'', she said of the theory that Sheldon has Asperger's:\n<blockquote>All of our characters are in theory on the neuropsychiatric spectrum, I would say. Sheldon often gets talked about in terms of Asperger\u2019s or OCD. He has a thing with germs, he has a thing with numbers, he\u2019s got a lot of that precision that we see in OCD. There\u2019s a lot of interesting features to all of our characters that make them technically unconventional socially.... And what we\u2019re trying to show with our show is that this is a group of people who likely were teased, mocked, told that they will never be appreciated or loved, and we have a group of people who have successful careers, active social lives (that involve things like Dungeons and Dragons and video games), but they also have relationships, and that\u2019s a fulfilling and satisfying life.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gill|first=Jim|title='Is Sheldon autistic? The Big Bang Theory actress Mayim Bialik gives this brilliant response'|publisher=Immediate Media Company|date=15 June 2015|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2015-06-15/is-sheldon-autistic-the-big-bang-theory-actress-mayim-bialik-gives-this-brilliant-response/|accessdate=January 12, 2018}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Comedy|Television|Physics}}\n{{The Big Bang Theory}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cooper, Sheldon}}\n[[Category:Fictional characters from Texas]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters from Pasadena, California]]\n[[Category:Television characters introduced in 2007]]\n[[Category:Fictional child prodigies]]\n[[Category:Atheism in television]]\n[[Category:Fictional Nobel laureates]]\n[[Category:Fictional theoretical physicists]]\n[[Category:Fictional twins]]\n[[Category:The Big Bang Theory characters]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters with eidetic memory]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters who became a protagonist in a spin-off]]\n[[Category:Child characters in television]]\n[[Category:Male characters in television]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7d:541f:4300:69d0:9c41:22eb:d2ec", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sheldon_Cooper"}
{"title_page": "Robert M. Lightfoot Jr.", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name           = Robert M. Lightfoot Jr.\n| image          = Robert M. Lightfoot Jr. official portrait.jpg\n| title          = Acting [[Administrator of the National Aeronautics and Space Administration]]\n| president      = [[Donald Trump]]\n| deputy         = [[Lesa Roe]] (acting)\n| term_start     = January 20, 2017\n| term_end       = April 23, 2018\n| predecessor    = [[Charles Bolden]]\n| successor      = [[Jim Bridenstine]]\n| office1        = Associate Administrator of the [[National Aeronautics and Space Administration]]\n| president1     = [[Barack Obama]]<br>Donald Trump\n| deputy1        = [[Lesa Roe]]<br/>[[Krista Paquin]]\n| term_start1    = September 25, 2012\n| term_end1      = April 30, 2018\n| predecessor1   = \n| successor1     = [[Stephen Jurczyk]] (Acting)\n| birth_date     = \n| birth_place    = [[Montevallo, Alabama|Montevallo]], [[Alabama]], U.S.\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| education      = [[University of Alabama]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])\n| spouse         = Caroline Smith<ref>http://history.msfc.nasa.gov/management/center_directors/pages/lightfoot.html</ref>\n| website        = [https://www.nasa.gov/about/highlights/lightfoot_bio.html NASA Biography]\n}}\n'''Robert M. Lightfoot Jr.''' is former [[List of Administrators and Deputy Administrators of NASA|Acting Administrator]] of the [[National Aeronautics and Space Administration]] (NASA), serving from January 20, 2017 until April 23, 2018, making him the longest-serving Acting Administrator in NASA history.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aviationweek.com/awin-only/lightfoot-radzanowski-will-head-nasa-temporarily|title=Lightfoot, Radzanowski Will Head NASA Temporarily|website=aviationweek.com}}</ref> He is also the incumbent Associate Administrator of NASA. Succeeding [[Charles Bolden]], Lightfoot became the space agency's acting Associate Administrator on March 5, 2012. That job became permanent on September 25, 2012. He had previously served as the eleventh Director of the [[NASA]] [[Marshall Space Flight Center]] in [[Huntsville, Alabama]], from March 2009 until his promotion in March 2012. On March 12, 2018 he announced his retirement from NASA effective April 30, 2018.\n\n==Early life==\nLightfoot has a bachelor's degree in mechanical engineering from the [[University of Alabama]].<ref name=\"hvt825\"/> In October 2007, he was named Distinguished Departmental Fellow for the University of Alabama, Department of Mechanical Engineering and selected as a University of Alabama College of Engineering fellow in 2009. Lightfoot serves on the University of Alabama Mechanical Engineering Advisory Board.<ref name=\"lightpr\">{{cite pressrelease |publisher=NASA |title=Lightfoot Named Director of NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center |url=http://www.nasa.gov/centers/marshall/news/news/releases/2009/H-09-195.html |date=August 24, 2009 |accessdate=August 30, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nLightfoot joined NASA in 1989 as a test engineer and program manager at Marshall.<ref name=\"hvt825\">{{cite news |first=Shelby G. |last=Spires |work=[[The Huntsville Times]] |title=Marshall keeps Lightfoot |url=http://www.al.com/news/huntsvilletimes/local.ssf?/base/news/1251191756326600.xml&coll=1 |date=August 25, 2009 |accessdate=August 30, 2009}}</ref>  In 1998, he was named deputy division chief of Marshall's propulsion test division.  Lightfoot moved to NASA's [[John C. Stennis Space Center]] in 1999 as chief of propulsion test operations. In 2001, he was named deputy director of the Propulsion Test Directorate at Stennis and in March 2002 he was promoted to director.<ref name=\"lightpr\"/><ref name=\"bish\">{{cite news |work=[[The Sun Herald]] |title=Stennis Ready to Respond to New Challenges |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BX&s_site=sunherald&p_multi=BX&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0FB3344FCA39AFBE&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |date=January 10, 2003 |accessdate=August 30, 2009 |page=18}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2003 to 2005, Lightfoot served as assistant associate administrator for the [[Space Shuttle Program]] in the Office of Space Operations at NASA Headquarters in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=\"lightpr\"/> He returned to Marshall in 2005 as manager of the Space Shuttle Propulsion Office.  In 2007, Lightfoot was named deputy director of Marshall where he shared responsibility for managing the center.<ref name=\"hnt19\">{{cite news |publisher=[[WHNT-TV]] News 19 |title=NASA Names Robert Lightfoot Director of Marshall Space Flight Center |url=http://www.whnt.com/whnt-robert-lightfoot-marshall-director,0,6147053.story |date=August 24, 2009 |accessdate=August 30, 2009}}</ref>  He served in that capacity until becoming acting director on March 26, 2009, after the retirement of the previous director, [[David A. King (engineer)|David A. King]].<ref name=\"kingpr\">{{cite press release |publisher=NASA |title=King Retires as Director of NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center |url=http://www.nasa.gov/home/hqnews/2009/mar/HQ_09-071_MSFC_King_Retires.html |date=March 26, 2009 |accessdate=August 30, 2009}}</ref> Lightfoot was formally named as the eleventh director of the Marshall Space Flight Center on August 24, 2009.<ref name=\"hnt19\"/> He led Marshall through the transition from the Shuttle era to the [[Space Launch System]].<ref name=\"ht110803\">{{cite news |first=Lee |last=Roop |work=[[The Huntsville Times]] |title=NASA's Marshall center reinventing itself after shuttle program |url=http://blog.al.com/space-news/2011/08/nasas_marshall_center_reinvent.html |date=August 3, 2011 |accessdate=August 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, NASA announced that Lightfoot would become the space agency's acting Associate Administrator as of March 5, 2012. The position opened when [[Chris Scolese]] was named the new director of the [[Goddard Space Flight Center]] in [[Greenbelt, Maryland]]. Lightfoot's successor at Marshall was [[Arthur E. Goldman|Arthur E. \"Gene\" Goldman]], named as acting director in March 2012.<ref name=\"pr120405\"/> Lightfoot shifted from acting to permanent Associate Administrator on September 25, 2012.<ref name=\"msfc120925\">{{cite press release |first=Jennifer |last=Stanfield |first2=David |last2=Weaver |publisher=[[NASA]] [[Marshall Space Flight Center]] |title=NASA Announces Senior Leadership Changes |url=http://www.nasa.gov/centers/marshall/news/news/releases/2012/H-12-335.html |date=September 25, 2012 |accessdate=November 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, 2018, Lightfoot announced that he would be retiring from the agency on April 30, 2018.<ref>[http://nasawatch.com/archives/2018/03/robert-lightfoo.html Retirement letter in NASAWatch]</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Lightfoot joined the Advisory Board of [[Firefly Aerospace]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Firefly Aerospace Announces Formation of Advisory Board |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/firefly-aerospace-announces-formation-of-advisory-board-300684342.html |accessdate=30 July 2018 |agency=CISION PR Newswire |date=30 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nA native of [[Montevallo, Alabama]], Lightfoot has received several awards during his career, including the [[Presidential Rank Award]] for Meritorious Executives in 2006 and a [[NASA Outstanding Leadership Medal]] in 2007 for \"outstanding and exemplary leadership of the Shuttle Propulsion Office\" and \"assuring safety for the shuttle's return to flight\".<ref name=\"lightpr\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"pr120405\">{{cite press release |first=Angela |last=Storey |agency=[[NASA]] |publisher=[[Marshall Space Flight Center]] |title=Russell, Miss., Native Arthur E. 'Gene' Goldman Named Acting Director of NASA's Marshall Center  |url=http://www.nasa.gov/centers/marshall/news/news/releases/2012/12-037.html |date=April 5, 2012 |accessdate=April 6, 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://history.msfc.nasa.gov/management/center_directors/pages/lightfoot.html NASA biography]\n*{{C-SPAN|robertlightfoot}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Associate Administrator of NASA|years=2012\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=Stephen Jurczyk<br>{{small|Acting}}}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Charles Bolden]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Administrator of NASA]]<br>{{small|Acting}}|years=2017\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jim Bridenstine]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{NASAadmin}}\n{{NASAMSFC}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lightfoot, Robert M. Jr.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Montevallo, Alabama]]\n[[Category:American mechanical engineers]]\n[[Category:Directors of the Marshall Space Flight Center]]\n[[Category:University of Alabama alumni]]\n[[Category:Administrators of NASA]]\n[[Category:Presidential Rank Award recipients]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name           = Robert M. Lightfoot Jr.\n| image          = Robert M. Lightfoot Jr. official portrait.jpg\n| title          = Acting [[Administrator of the National Aeronautics and Space Administration]]\n| president      = [[Donald Trump]]\n| deputy         = [[Lesa Roe]] (acting)\n| term_start     = January 20, 2017\n| term_end       = April 23, 2018\n| predecessor    = [[Charles Bolden]]\n| successor      = [[Jim Bridenstine]]\n| office1        = Associate Administrator of the [[National Aeronautics and Space Administration]]\n| president1     = [[Barack Obama]]<br>Donald Trump\n| deputy1        = [[Lesa Roe]]<br/>[[Krista Paquin]]\n| term_start1    = September 25, 2012\n| term_end1      = April 30, 2018\n| predecessor1   = \n| successor1     = [[Stephen Jurczyk]] (Acting)\n| birth_date     = \n| birth_place    = [[Montevallo, Alabama|Montevallo]], [[Alabama]], U.S.\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| education      = [[University of Alabama]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])\n| spouse         = Caroline Smith<ref>http://history.msfc.nasa.gov/management/center_directors/pages/lightfoot.html</ref>\n| website        = [https://www.nasa.gov/about/highlights/lightfoot_bio.html NASA Biography]\n}}\n'''Robert M. Lightfoot Jr.''' is former [[List of Administrators and Deputy Administrators of NASA|Acting Administrator]] of the [[National Aeronautics and Space Administration]] (NASA), serving from January 20, 2017 until April 23, 2018, making him the longest-serving Acting Administrator in NASA history.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://aviationweek.com/awin-only/lightfoot-radzanowski-will-head-nasa-temporarily|title=Lightfoot, Radzanowski Will Head NASA Temporarily|website=aviationweek.com}}</ref> He is also the incumbent Associate Administrator of NASA. Succeeding [[Charles Bolden]], Lightfoot became the space agency's acting Associate Administrator on March 5, 2012. That job became permanent on September 25, 2012. He had previously served as the eleventh Director of the [[NASA]] [[Marshall Space Flight Center]] in [[Huntsville, Alabama]], from March 2009 until his promotion in March 2012. On March 12, 2018 he announced his retirement from NASA effective April 30, 2018.\n\n==Early life==\nLightfoot has a bachelor's degree in mechanical engineering from the [[University of Alabama]].<ref name=\"hvt825\"/> In October 2007, he was named Distinguished Departmental Fellow for the University of Alabama, Department of Mechanical Engineering and selected as a University of Alabama College of Engineering fellow in 2009. Lightfoot serves on the University of Alabama Mechanical Engineering Advisory Board.<ref name=\"lightpr\">{{cite pressrelease |publisher=NASA |title=Lightfoot Named Director of NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center |url=http://www.nasa.gov/centers/marshall/news/news/releases/2009/H-09-195.html |date=August 24, 2009 |accessdate=August 30, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nLightfoot joined NASA in 1989 as a test engineer and program manager at Marshall.<ref name=\"hvt825\">{{cite news |first=Shelby G. |last=Spires |work=[[The Huntsville Times]] |title=Marshall keeps Lightfoot |url=http://www.al.com/news/huntsvilletimes/local.ssf?/base/news/1251191756326600.xml&coll=1 |date=August 25, 2009 |accessdate=August 30, 2009}}</ref>  In 1998, he was named deputy division chief of Marshall's propulsion test division.  Lightfoot moved to NASA's [[John C. Stennis Space Center]] in 1999 as chief of propulsion test operations. In 2001, he was named deputy director of the Propulsion Test Directorate at Stennis and in March 2002 he was promoted to director.<ref name=\"lightpr\"/><ref name=\"bish\">{{cite news |work=[[The Sun Herald]] |title=Stennis Ready to Respond to New Challenges |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BX&s_site=sunherald&p_multi=BX&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0FB3344FCA39AFBE&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |date=January 10, 2003 |accessdate=August 30, 2009 |page=18}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2003 to 2005, Lightfoot served as assistant associate administrator for the [[Space Shuttle Program]] in the Office of Space Operations at NASA Headquarters in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=\"lightpr\"/> He returned to Marshall in 2005 as manager of the Space Shuttle Propulsion Office.  In 2007, Lightfoot was named deputy director of Marshall where he shared responsibility for managing the center.<ref name=\"hnt19\">{{cite news |publisher=[[WHNT-TV]] News 19 |title=NASA Names Robert Lightfoot Director of Marshall Space Flight Center |url=http://www.whnt.com/whnt-robert-lightfoot-marshall-director,0,6147053.story |date=August 24, 2009 |accessdate=August 30, 2009}}</ref>  He served in that capacity until becoming acting director on March 26, 2009, after the retirement of the previous director, [[David A. King (engineer)|David A. King]].<ref name=\"kingpr\">{{cite press release |publisher=NASA |title=King Retires as Director of NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center |url=http://www.nasa.gov/home/hqnews/2009/mar/HQ_09-071_MSFC_King_Retires.html |date=March 26, 2009 |accessdate=August 30, 2009}}</ref> Lightfoot was formally named as the eleventh director of the Marshall Space Flight Center on August 24, 2009.<ref name=\"hnt19\"/> He led Marshall through the transition from the Shuttle era to the [[Space Launch System]].<ref name=\"ht110803\">{{cite news |first=Lee |last=Roop |work=[[The Huntsville Times]] |title=NASA's Marshall center reinventing itself after shuttle program |url=http://blog.al.com/space-news/2011/08/nasas_marshall_center_reinvent.html |date=August 3, 2011 |accessdate=August 3, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, NASA announced that Lightfoot would become the space agency's acting Associate Administrator as of March 5, 2012. The position opened when [[Chris Scolese]] was named the new director of the [[Goddard Space Flight Center]] in [[Greenbelt, Maryland]]. Lightfoot's successor at Marshall was [[Arthur E. Goldman|Arthur E. \"Gene\" Goldman]], named as acting director in March 2012.<ref name=\"pr120405\"/> He, Lightfoot, shifted from acting to permanent Associate Administrator on September 25, 2012.<ref name=\"msfc120925\">{{cite press release |first=Jennifer |last=Stanfield |first2=David |last2=Weaver |publisher=[[NASA]] [[Marshall Space Flight Center]] |title=NASA Announces Senior Leadership Changes |url=http://www.nasa.gov/centers/marshall/news/news/releases/2012/H-12-335.html |date=September 25, 2012 |accessdate=November 28, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, 2018, Lightfoot announced that he would be retiring from the agency on April 30, 2018.<ref>[http://nasawatch.com/archives/2018/03/robert-lightfoo.html Retirement letter in NASAWatch]</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, Lightfoot joined the Advisory Board of [[Firefly Aerospace]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Firefly Aerospace Announces Formation of Advisory Board |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/firefly-aerospace-announces-formation-of-advisory-board-300684342.html |accessdate=30 July 2018 |agency=CISION PR Newswire |date=30 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nA native of [[Montevallo, Alabama]], Lightfoot has received several awards during his career, including the [[Presidential Rank Award]] for Meritorious Executives in 2006 and a [[NASA Outstanding Leadership Medal]] in 2007 for \"outstanding and exemplary leadership of the Shuttle Propulsion Office\" and \"assuring safety for the shuttle's return to flight\".<ref name=\"lightpr\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"pr120405\">{{cite press release |first=Angela |last=Storey |agency=[[NASA]] |publisher=[[Marshall Space Flight Center]] |title=Russell, Miss., Native Arthur E. 'Gene' Goldman Named Acting Director of NASA's Marshall Center  |url=http://www.nasa.gov/centers/marshall/news/news/releases/2012/12-037.html |date=April 5, 2012 |accessdate=April 6, 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://history.msfc.nasa.gov/management/center_directors/pages/lightfoot.html NASA biography]\n*{{C-SPAN|robertlightfoot}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Associate Administrator of NASA|years=2012\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=Stephen Jurczyk<br>{{small|Acting}}}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Charles Bolden]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Administrator of NASA]]<br>{{small|Acting}}|years=2017\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jim Bridenstine]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{NASAadmin}}\n{{NASAMSFC}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lightfoot, Robert M. Jr.}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Montevallo, Alabama]]\n[[Category:American mechanical engineers]]\n[[Category:Directors of the Marshall Space Flight Center]]\n[[Category:University of Alabama alumni]]\n[[Category:Administrators of NASA]]\n[[Category:Presidential Rank Award recipients]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n", "name_user": "1990'sguy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_M._Lightfoot_Jr."}
